<HEADLINE> France Lowers Banking Rate in Expectation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- France Thursday decided to lower
its key banking interest rate, the tenders rate, from 3.3 percent
to 3.0 percent, in expectation of slower growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The French central bank, Banque de France, said that the
decision was made in concertation with other European central
banks and is aimed at keeping the confidence of households and
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Another key interest rate, the short-term borrowing rate, is
kept unchanged at 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The president of the board of management of Banque de France,
Jean-Claude Trichet, said that the international environment
remains uncertain and a certain slowdown in the growth is expected
in the whole euro zone in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the stability of the French franc and the
European single currency euro will be ensured.
</P>
<P>
The French Minister of Finance and Economy Dominique
Strauss-Kahn said on Wednesday for the first time that the French
economy is not on the ``slope'' of 2.7 percent as is previously
expected for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the French franc with the U.S. dollar has
remained over-valued for months at around one dollar for 5.7
francs.
</P>
<P>
The single currency will be formally launched one month later
by 11 countries of the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
