<HEADLINE> Former Ukrainian PM Arrested in Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's former prime minister
Pavlo Lazarenko was brought to Geneva Thursday for investigation
after being arrested in the northern Swiss city of Basle when he
entered Switzerland in a car from France Wednesday, according to
the Swiss news agency, ATS.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said that 45-year-old Lazarenko and his aid
were wanted by Ukrainian authorities on suspicion of having
embezzled public money worth 20 million U.S. dollars and deposited
in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko, prime minister from June 1996 to June 1997, is now a
parliamentary deputy and heads the influential Hromada (Community)
left-center movement which strongly opposes President Leonid
Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kiev cited the president of the commission for
foreign affairs as saying that Ukraine is waiting for the
explanations about Lazarenko's arrest from the Swiss authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
