<HEADLINE> Turkish PM-Designate to Form Left-Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
designate Bulent Ecevit said here Thursday that the 56th cabinet
would be a left-right coalition of three parties.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, leader of the center-left Democratic Left Party (DSP),
made the announcement at the DSP group meeting in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said he will explore the possibility of a troika cabinet
which comprises his party and two center-right parties, the
Motherland Party (ANAP) led by ousted prime minister Mesut Yilmaz
and the True Path Party (DYP) led by former prime minister Tansu
Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel on Wednesday asked
Ecevit to form the new government, saying that "it is possible
for Ecevit to gain a confidence vote in the parliament."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who was deputy prime minister in the 55th government
collapsed last week over a corruption scandal, has served as prime
minister three times since 1974.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, a former correspondent, was born in Istanbul, the
largest city of Turkey, in 1925.
</P>
