<HEADLINE> International Symposium on DU Impacts Concludes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- People who were affected by
depleted uranium (DU) in the 1991 Gulf War should be compensated,
said a statement issued here Thursday at the conclusion of an
international symposium on the use of DU and its impacts on man
and environment.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, which started on Wednesday,
participants discussed the grave effects of the U.S.-British use
of banned DU shells against Iraq on its coming generations and on
other states in the region.
</P>
<P>
The symposium brought together more than 200 experts and
specialists from the U.S., Britain, Canada, Germany, Jordan,
Tunisia and Iraq, and some U.S. and British veterans who had
participated in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Two sessions were held Thursday to discuss scientific research
findings on the issue. One research indicates that large
landscapes in southern Iraq have been polluted by DU radiations,
referring to the increase in cancer cases among Iraqi soldiers,
especially the spread of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
Another research shows that barrenness cases have more
than doubled in the Iraqi province of Basrah, and at the
same time, cases of congenital deformities have also doubled,
notably in the southern provinces.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. allegations that the Gulf War was a clean war
were not true, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait in August 1990, touching off the
1991 Gulf War. During the 43-day war, the U.S. and Britain
dropped some 700-800 tons of DU shells in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
