<HEADLINE> Annan to Meet Libyan Leader on Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will meet with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi on
Saturday to discuss the 1988 Lockerbie airliner bombing, a U.N.
spokesman said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva told a press
conference that Annan revealed the planned visit on Thursday after
meeting with Tunisian Foreign Minister Said Ben Mustapha in Tunis,
capital of Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted the U.N. chief as saying at a news
conference in Tunis, "Yes, I will go to Libya on Saturday. We are
going to look at solutions to the problem." Asked if he would meet
Gaddafi, Annan replied, "Yes, I believe so."
</P>
<P>
"Of course, he (Annan) was to help improve and find good
results and solve an impasse," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Annan on Wednesday asked a Security Council sanctions committee
for permission to break a U.N. air embargo and fly either to
Tripoli, the Libyan capital, or Sirte, a coastal city some 450
kilometers east of Triopli, U.N. sources said. The spokesman also
confirmed that Annan has got permission from the committee to go
ahead with his flight into Libya.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. spokesman, asked about where Annan would meet
with Gaddafi, told reporters that "the details of the trip at this
point must be kept confidential at least a while longer."
</P>
<P>
Libyan lawyers and the U.N. legal team, which spent several
weeks in New York, have discussed the matters on the surrender of
the two suspects in the Lockerbie bombing, which took place nearly
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Libya has agreed to put the two suspects, namely Abdel Basset
Ali Mohammed al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, on trial in the
Netherlands before a Scottish court. But Tripoli has objected to
British and U.S. demands that they serve their sentences in
Scotland if convicted.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans have been accused by the United States and
Britain of planting a bomb aboard Pan Am Flight 303 which
exploded over the Scottish village of Lockerbie in December
1988, killing 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
