<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary Calls for Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley ended a one-day visit here Thursday with strong
call for improved trade and investment environment in Africa
which will expand U.S.-African economic relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Your economic house must be in order. Companies look at the
fundamentals of government policies... and I encourage all of you
to help promote a more transparent, open, better environment for
doing business," he told economic leaders from Uganda, Tanzania
and Kenya at a luncheon here.
</P>
<P>
He urged the continent to make more efforts to "build on the
progress to date in privatizing and cutting trade barriers," to
maintain political stability, improve infrastructure and legal
structure, as well as promote regional trade.
</P>
<P>
"For Africa to be on a global stage, it cannot be small
disconnected markets. It must be regional markets... But today,
only 13 percent of African trade is with other African
countries," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Later at a press conference, he said that he is optismistic
about the prospect of the two-way trade between Africa and
America especially as the Clinton administration may push the
African Growth and Opportunity Act through Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
"I am optimistic that the African Growth and Opportunity Act
will go through, and I believe... that it will go through next
year," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The bill to promote trade and investment in Africa was passed
by the U.N. House of Representatives in March, but got stalled
before the Senate Finance Committee in July after a series of
amendments were attached to it.
</P>
<P>
Daley's visit, the second to Kenya and the third to Africa
this year, is widely seen as a clear signal that the U.S. is
trying hard to re-focus its relationship with the poorest
continent from politics to economy.
</P>
<P>
Daley, who flies to Cote d'Ivoire on Thursday evening, was
accompanied by a 15-strong delegation of American corporate
executives including those from AT&AMP;T, Chevron, Dupont, Cargill,
Kodak and Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
Four commercial cooperation agreements were signed Thursday
between the U.S. companies and the Kenyan side on agricultural
research, investment fund, industrial standard and aviation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Export-Import Bank signed an accord on financing
Kenya Airways Ltd. to purchase a Boeing 737-300 aircraft from
America.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Kenyan Trade Ministry show that in 1997, Kenya
imported 705.49 million Shillings (around 102 million U.S.
Dollars) of U.S. goods and and exported goods worth of 170.07
million Shillings (some 28.3 million Dollars) to the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
