<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Exert Efforts to Boost Coffee Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Coffee and Tea
Authority said Thursday that it is exerting maximum efforts to
boost the revenue from coffee export.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Tsegaye Berhane,
General Manager of the authority, told journalists that a slump
in the world coffee price is feared in 1998/99 as a result of
high production of the crop in coffee producing countries like
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Tsegaye said that a slump in the world price of coffee could
have a domino effect on the price of Ethiopia coffee in the
international auction.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is Ethiopia's most important export commodity and
contributes to about 60 percent of the export income.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Minister of Trade and Industry Kasahun Ayele
announced here last month that the income from coffee export
takes a 63.6 percent share of its export planned in 1998/99 (July
8, 1998-July 7, 1999).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tsegaye urged the coffee producers and traders not
to keep the crop in storage for an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
A sizable quantity of coffee is kept in storage by Ethiopian
farmers and traders, according to the authority.
</P>
<P>
"If coffee is stored for a long time, it will lose its quality
and taste," the general manager said, adding that "this will, in
turn, have a dire consequence on the value of Ethiopian coffee in
the world market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
