<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Trade Account Improves: C. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade account
during October improved by 33 percent, reducing deficit by 26.5
million U.S. Dollars over the previous month, the Bank of
Tanzania said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This improvement was largely due to an increase in export
earnings by 67.2 percent, which more than offset the effect of
1.9 percent increase in import bill, the central bank said in its
latest monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
The increase in export earnings originated from the
traditional sector whose earnings more than doubled, said the
November issue report.
</P>
<P>
During the year ending October 1998, the trade account
recorded a deficit of 788.3 million Dollars, representing a 28.5
percent increase compared with a deficit of 613.6 million Dollars
recorded during the corresponding period last year, it added.
</P>
<P>
The trade account deficit worsened during the reviewing period
primarily because of a significant decline in export earnings
coupled with an increase of the import bill, it said. 
</P>
