<HEADLINE> Retail Confidence Falls in Britain at Record Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) - Confidence in high street sales
among British retailers is falling at its fastest rate since
records began 15 years ago, according to a survey by The
Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
Sales volumes were down, with only 36 percent of shops
reporting an increase compared with the same time last year and 45
percent experiencing a dip.
</P>
<P>
The CBI found that falling sales in November took retailers by
surprise and led them drastically to cut their expectations.
</P>
<P>
It said the survey underlined the need for a further cut in
interest rates at the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee
meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate director of economic
analysis, said the results "underlined the message from other
data, that demand at home is softening, supporting the need for a
0.5 percent cut in interest rates next week."
</P>
<P>
The survey came on the day that another poll found the service
sector as a whole had contracted for the first time in at least
two years.
</P>
<P>
The November Chartered Institute of Purchasing Managers' report
found business activity decreased for the first time since the
survey began in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
