<HEADLINE> Britain Denies Paying for Charges against Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The British embassy in Cairo on
Thursday denied that it was channeling money to an Egyptian human
rights group for a report on alleged religious persecution in the
country.
</P>
<P>
An embassy spokesman said the claim that the money sent to the
Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) was payment for its
report on Egyptian police torture of Christian Copts in the south
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
That the embassy relaying a check of 25,703 U.S. dollars
offered by the British Foreign Office to EOHR "has nothing to do
with" that report, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to Egypt's Middle East News Agency, the spokesman
said that Britain has contributed to EOHR during the past two
years, including the latest sum, and the funds were intended to
help finance an EOHR program to provide legal aid for Egyptian
women.
</P>
<P>
The British embassy's denial came after the Al Usbou weekly
newspaper maintained that the check that EOHR recently received
from the embassy was behind its report.
</P>
<P>
The private-owned weekly denounced EOHR's acceptance of the
money as treason, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
EOHR, founded in 1985, decided a week ago to send back the
check to the British embassy.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette newspaper has reported that EOHR released
a report in September claiming that more than 1,000 Copts were
rounded up by police at Kosheh village in southern Suhag
Governorate.
</P>
<P>
Based on the allegation, Britain's Sunday Telegraph newspaper
said: "Egyptian Christians have been subjected to horrific
crucification rituals, raped and tortured by the security forces
during a crackdown on the ancient Coptic community."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's parliament, social groups and celebrities have
denounced the story in the British newspaper as a fabrication
aimed at defaming Egypt.
</P>
<P>
They said Muslim majority and Christian minority have been
peacefully co-existing for more than 14 centuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
