<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Rival Warlords Back From Soliciting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Somalis with
green leaves, placards, flags, guns and battle wagons Thursday
headed toward the dusty airstrips of Jasira and Km-50 to receive
the two rival Somali warlords, Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Osman
Ali Atto.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 battle wagons and senior officials from the
disputed administration of Mogadishu welcomed Hussein Mohamed
Aidid at Km-50 after he has been out of Somalia for nearly four
months.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid did not speak to the people over his journey.
However, it is known that he went out to normalize his relation
with the government of Ethiopia and to seek moral and material
support for the administration he created with his former arch
rival Ali Mahdi Mohamed in early August this year.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid has visited Addis Ababa of Ethiopia, Yemen,
Egypt and Libya where he met the leaders of the countries over
the possible ways they could assist the administration of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
More than 800,000 U.S. Dollars in cash, medicines and police
uniforms have already reached the capital in his absence as the
first signs of moral support from those countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite all these donations and the demobilization of three
thousand militiamen, the security situation in Mogadishu still
remains far from stable.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, faction leader Osman Ali Atto has landed from the
dusty and narrow airstrip of Jasira, 7 km south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Osman Ali Atto left Mogadishu a few days after the
establishment of Mogadishu's administration which he rejected its
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
Osman Atto, together with other political opponents of
Mogadishu's administration, have been lobbying for blocking any
political recognition or material support for Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the two warlords in Mogadishu Thursday is not a
mere coincidence, but a tactful act in which both men are
preparing to meet the international delegation currently visiting
Somalia for the assessment of a possible reconciliation and
reconstruction for Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The delegation which is due to arrive in Mogadishu in two
or three days is not likely to be smooth going in their attempts
to meet the political rivals, business rivals, religious rivals,
rival traditional elders as well as rival Islamic courts.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming delegation has already affected Mogadishu
where the value of international currencies are decreasing
considerably.
</P>
<P>
The administration of Somaliland has already met the
delegation while others like Puntland, Mogadishu and Hiran are on
the schedule to meet them, with political rivals also looking
forward to the meeting with the aim of telling them their own
views and efforts in reconciling and rebuilding a better Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Politicians foresee that those groups will in the end manage
to confuse the delegation, since each group is pretending to be
the largest and most significant, and a solution for Somalia's
crises will remain as difficult as ever unless a strong decision
is taken by the international community toward the formation of a
central administration for Somalia if it will ever come into
existence in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
