<HEADLINE> U.N. General Assembly Asked to Debate Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has officially informed
the United Nations that it would request a debate on the Cyprus
issue at the General Assembly in 1999, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' permanent representative to the U.N., Sotos Zackheos,
has told General Assembly President Didier Opertti on Wednesday of
the decision, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by Cyprus's National Council, the top
advisory body to the president, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. secretary-general's envoy in Cyprus, Ann Hercus, began
separate meetings with Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots in
October to ease the tensions on the island, Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
The protracted Cyprus problem was frequently discussed by the
U.N. Security Council, but has not been the subject of a General
Assembly debate since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Peace efforts have come to a standstill since the summer of
1997, when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash demanded
international recognition of his breakaway state in northern
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded that Cyprus withdraw its application to join
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
