<HEADLINE> Liberia's 1999 Draft Budget Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has proposed a balanced 1999 budget to parliament,
with spending up by 55 percent over 1998, a report reaching here
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget, proposed to the Liberian parliament Wednesday,
projected spending of 2.6 billion Liberian Dollars, or 64 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said the government would cover spending from revenue
without foreign help. "This shows that we have improved a little
bit over our revenue collection," he said.
</P>
<P>
He proposed the creation of a budget allotment committee to
ensure the funds are used for what they are intended.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said there would be no tax increase but efforts would
be made to improve the collection of existing taxes.
</P>
<P>
He also announced the cuts in official visits abroad and in
the number of Liberian embassies.
</P>
<P>
The embassy in South Africa will be responsible for southern
Africa, while Europe will be covered by an ambassador to the
European Union, the report added. 
</P>
