<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Calls for End to Circumcision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has urged Sabiny people in eastern districts to change
the culture of circumcising women and to appreciate that the
practice is dangerous medically and creates numerous health
problems for women.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said Museveni made
the appeal Thursday when addressing a public rally during his
one-day visit to the Kapchorwa district which coincided with the
celebrations to mark the district's Culture Day.
</P>
<P>
Culture, like all living things, has to grow and change if it
is to remain healthy and that his government has approached the
issue of women circumcision through education, sensitization and
dialog rather than legislation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He thanked Sabiny elders and organizations such as the United
Nations Fund for Population Activities for helping the government
in the campaign against female circumcision.
</P>
<P>
Female circumcision in the Sabiny tribe, which has been
observed for centuries, is considered by local people as a sign
of reaching womanhood. The fight against this old tradition won
a U.N. prize for the Sabiny leader recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
