<HEADLINE> Tanzania Export Earnings Rise by 67.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's total export
earnings during October increased by 67.1 percent to 71.9 million
U.S. Dollars, compared with 43 million U.S. Dollars recorded
during the previous month, the central bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A monthly economic review report by the Bank of Tanzania (BoT)
largely attributed the rise to a significant increase in earnings
from traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from traditional exports increased by 184.2 percent
to 42 million Dollars in October, compared with 14.8 million
Dollars recorded in the previous month, the November issue report
said.
</P>
<P>
Increases in both prices and volumes explain the improvement,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Except for cotton and sisal, whose volumes declined by 13.3
percent and 21.4 percent respectively, all other traditional
exports, namely coffee, tea, tobacco and cashewnut recorded
significant increases in export volumes, the report said, adding
that all crops recorded unit price increases during the period
under review.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, it said, earnings from non-traditional
exports increased by 5.9 percent to 29.9 million U.S. Dollars
from 28.3 million U.S. Dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
There was an increase in export earnings from petroleum
products, manufactured tobacco, fish and fish products,
horticultural produce and other exports, while all other
non-traditional exports, namely minerals, manufactured goods,
cotton yarn, manufactured coffee and sisal products recorded
declines in export earnings.
</P>
<P>
However, earnings from traditional exports decreased to 329.6
million U.S. Dollars, from 377.6 million recorded during the same
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's total imports in October increased by
two percent to 125.7 million U.S. Dollars, from 123.3 million
U.S. Dollars recorded during the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
