<HEADLINE> OECD Says Rules for International Investment Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) said Thursday that it is
necessary to establish rules for international investment.
</P>
<P>
But senior OECD officials failed to agree at an informal
meeting Thursday in Paris to resume talks on a Multilateral
Agreement on Investment (MAI), which went into a deadlock last
December because of a boycott by France.
</P>
<P>
France wishes to protect the domestic cultural market from an
overwhelming influence from the United States by imposing
restrictions on investment by U.S. audio and video products
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The OECD said in a communique that its 29 member countries have
agreed to work on the rules for investment which will be first
applied within its member countries.
</P>
<P>
"There exist in fact a certain number of important issues which
need new analysis and inter-governmental cooperation," said the
communique.
</P>
<P>
Some hope that the talks on MAI should be transferred to the
World Trade Organization, but the proposal has met with opposition
from some developing countries which are against imposition of
international rules on investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
