<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend MONUA's Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday decided to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) until February 26,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision came in a resolution adopted unanimously by the
15-member Security Council after it considered a report on the
current situation in Angola by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demanded that the rebel UNITA "comply
immediately and without conditions with its obligations, in
particular the complete demilitarization of its forces and full
cooperation in the immediate and unconditional extension of state
administration throughout the national territory."
</P>
<P>
The resolution called on the leadership of UNITA to "cooperate
fully and immediately" with the MONUA in the withdrawal of the
U.N. mission personnel from the conflict-hit areas of Andulo and
Bailundo, and held the leadership of the rebel group "responsible
for their safety and security."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said in the resolution that "the primary
cause of the crisis in Angola and of the current impasse in the
peace process is the failure by the leadership of UNITA in
Bailundo to comply with its obligations" under the peace accords
and relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was sponsored by Portugal, Russia and the United
States, the three countries which are in a group to monitor the
peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Angolan government has agreed to
the extension of the mandate of the MONUA until February next
year.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council last week, Annan said
that "the overall political, military and security situation in
the country has further deteriorated. The dialogue between the
government and (Jonas) Savimbi and his movement has ceased."
</P>
<P>
The MONUA was sent into Angola under a Security Council
resolution on June 30, 1997 to monitor the peace process in the
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
