<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Increases Trade Ties with Asian Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The 15 European Union (EU)
countries have increased more imports from 11 Asian countries and
areas. EU's trade deficit with the Asia region rose last year to
31 billion ECU (some 34 billion U.S. dollars) from 16.2 billion
ECU (17.8 U.S. dollars) in 1996, according to EU's statistics
available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 11 Asian countries and areas are China, Japan, South Korea,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Brunei
and Vietnam, as well as China' Hong Kong. They have been denoted
as Asia 11 since they participated in the Asia-Europe Meeting
(ASEM) in London in April this year, the statistics report said.
</P>
<P>
The 15 European countries' imports of goods from the Asia 11
amounted to 168.3 billion ECU (185.1 billion U.S.dollars) in 1997
while their exports to the Asia 11 region totalled 132.8 billion
ECU (146 billion U.S. dollars). The report showed the
corresponding figures for 1996 were 139.3 billion ECU (153.2
billion U.S. dollars) and 123.1 billion ECU (135.4 billion
U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report said the negative balance overall last year comes
mainly from that of the Britain (-15.3 billion ECU) and the
Netherlands (-13.9 billion ECU), while small positive balances
recorded by some other EU member states were not enough to
compensate.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the EU deficit resulted from large negative balances
with Japan (-23.3 billion ECU) and China (-20.09 billion ECU). But
the large deficit was offset by a positive balance of 12.1 billion
ECU with Hong Kong, the report shows.
</P>
<P>
During last year, both EU's imports and exports from and to the
Asian 11 region were concentrated in machinery and transport
equipment, which accounted for over half of all trade. These
products, together with miscellaneous manufactures, were
responsible for the EU being over 30 billion ECU (33 billion
U.S.dollars) in the red, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also showed that imports to the EU from Asia 11
came mainly from Japan (36.2 percent), ASEAN (28 percent) and
China (22.8 percent), which represent 17.6 percent up from 1996 to
1997, higher than the rise of 14.9 percent in extra-EU imports in
general.
</P>
<P>
This "implies an increasing share of Asia 11 in extra-EU
imports", the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
