<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria to Intensify Consultations on Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Algeria would intensify
consultations with other members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) on ways to raise oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Minister of Energy and Mines Youcef Yousfi, who is
current chief of the OPEC, made the remark Thursday in a press
briefing on the fringe of an international conference on gas now
in session here, the Algerian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The current price slump is very serious for the oil producing
countries, which lost some 80 billion U.S. dollars this year, he
said. Algeria alone incurred a loss somewhere between 2.5 and 3
billion, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The main factors of the crisis, he said, are the heated
speculations after the OPEC meeting in Vienna on November 26
failed to agree upon new cuts in oil production and the weak
demand on the oil market this winter.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the OPEC members were in favor of production
cuts to curb the imbalance of the oil market, but differences on
the production cut quotas blocked any new resolutions during the
meeting, Yousfi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
