<HEADLINE> Livingston Wants Impeachment Inquiry Completed This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Incoming Speaker Bob
Livingston made clear Thursday he wants the U.S. House of
Representatives to vote on impeachment by year's end.
</P>
<P>
"I can't say I'd be perfectly happy" if the fight extends into
the new year, Livingston said during a news conference with Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott. He said that could happen only if
impeachment investigators didn't wrap up work by next week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House lawyers are preparing a "vigorous
defense" of Clinton and demanding sensitive fund-raising memos and
other material gathered by Republican investigators.
</P>
<P>
Livingston said it is too early to make any decision on whether
the House should consider censuring Clinton as an alternative to
impeachment -- an option that has some support in both parties.
"I'm just not going to make a decision on that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde told Republican members
in a conference call Thursday morning that the staff review of
Justice Department memos detailing alleged fund-raising
irregularities in Clinton's campaign in 1996 did not yield
information worth considering for articles of impeachment, several
committee officials said.
</P>
<P>
"The evidence from the Department of Justice being examined in
relation to possible campaign finance violations will not be a
part of the inquiry next week," Representative Asa Hutchinson, a
Republican, said through his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Representative Peter King, a Republican, was circulating a
censure proposal Thursday. It would include a strong condemnation
of Clinton and require him to pay a financial penalty and issue a
statement acknowledging wrongdoing, according to King's spokesman,
Kevin Fogarty.
</P>
<P>
Livingston told reporters he had discussed impeachment briefly
in meetings this week with House Majority Leader Dick Armey and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
The White House legal team accepted an invitation from the
Judiciary Committee Wednesday to make a defense before the inquiry
next Tuesday and possibly even call witnesses, but demanded access
to the fund-raising memos and additional investigative material
related to Monica Lewinsky and Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
The Judiciary Committee is preparing for four days of hearings
next week, beginning with the White House defense and ending with
possible votes on at least one article of impeachment. If such a
proposal passes, the full House is likely to vote the following
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
