<HEADLINE> S. Africa's New Coach Shares His Vision for Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's newly
appointed national soccer coach Trott Moloto has indicated that
the winds of change would soon blow through the entire national
coaching set-up, with more emphasis on youth.
</P>
<P>
Moloto also pledged to improve the quality of national team's
strikers, saying the inability of the strikers to perform
adequately at international level is cause for concern, The
Citizen paper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moloto, who has been care-taker coach of the national side
since the end of this year's World Cup, was appointed on Thursday
as national head coach until March 2000, beyond the African
Nations Cup finals in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"My priority is to make sure Bafana (the national side)
qualify for the African Nations Cup finals in 2000," he said.
South Africans lost to Egyptians in the African Nations Cup final
in February this year.
</P>
<P>
"But of equal importance is to develop and expand SAFA (South
African Football Association)'s youth policy from under-13 right
to the top. The youth are our future and we have to encourage
them."
</P>
<P>
Moloto, who was once national under-17 coach, said he aims to
have a fine blend of youth and experience in the side.
</P>
<P>
Moloto said he will not tolerate breaches of discipline such
as were seen in the World Cup finals in France, and the only
criteria for selection will be current form.
</P>
<P>
"Reputations and past successes will count for nothing... I
will bring a new spirit to the team. I want the players to look
to me as a father figure to trust and respect," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moloto is expected to show his hand in this regard when he
names an 18-man squad on Monday, which will play Egypt in the
Nelson Mandela Challenge in Johannesburg on December 16.
</P>
<P>
In another step to avoid a repeat of the problems which
bedevilled the national team in recent years, Moloto disclosed
that he plans to have national B-team on stand-by, which is made
up purely of locally-based players.
</P>
<P>
This is to ensure if the overseas-based players are not being
released by their clubs for national duty, he will not be left in
a lurch.
</P>
<P>
Moloto, who will announce his new technical staff on January
1, will not be looking overseas for help.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see the need. We have good coaches in South Africa
who I can turn to for assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moloto started his coaching career in 1985 as assistant coach
at a local premier league club. He had been assistant to the two
previous national coaches since early this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
