<HEADLINE> UK Government Condemns Violence in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The British Government on Friday
condemned the violence between loyalist Orangemen and police
officers at Drumcree in Northern Ireland on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The Security Minister Adam Ingram said the incident was "a
throwback to behavior that the great majority of people in
Northern Ireland want an end to."
</P>
<P>
"The issues surrounding Drumcree cannot be resolved by riot and
violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ingram added the only way forward was through dialogue and by
reaching an agreed accommodation at local level, he said. The
government was doing everything it could to achieve that outcome.
</P>
<P>
The trouble flared near Drumcree Church among a 1,000-strong
crowd demonstrating in support of Orangemen involved in the
stand-off with police. The Orangemen insisted on walking down the
flashpoint nationalist Garvaghy Road before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
During the clashes loyalist rioters attacked police with
bricks, wooden stakes and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
A police officer fired a plastic baton round to try to scatter
rioters throwing missiles.
</P>
<P>
Four protesters were treated in hospital. They included a
20-year-old woman who suffered a broken wrist and a 72-year-old
man who was hit in the eye.
</P>
<P>
Ten police officers were hurt but none of them seriously and
there were no arrests.
</P>
<P>
The Drumcree protesters said they were more determined than
ever to hold their banned traditional parade and would stay put
during Christmas Day if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
