<HEADLINE> Sweden Confirms Secret Middle East Talks in Stockholm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Swedish Minister of Foreign
Affairs Anna Lindh said Friday that Palestine and Israel have been
holding secret talks in Stockholm since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks held in the past four years in
her country were of great importance to the Middle East peace
process, Lindh said.
</P>
<P>
The minister voiced hope that the talks would help pave the way
for peace in the region, but she didn't release details of
previous talks.
</P>
<P>
With the former Minister of Foreign Affairs Sten Andersson
acting as a go-between, Israel and Palestine began their secret
talks in Stockholm four years ago when they concluded the famous
Oslo talk, according to the Tidningarnas Telegrambyra, the Swedish
news agency.
</P>
<P>
The two sides focused their talks on issues such as the Jewish
settlement, the repatriation of refugees, and the status of
Jerusalem, the agency quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
No information was revealed about the people attending the
secret talks. It is reportedly too sensative a problem that could
affect the continuation of such talks.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is scheduled to visit
Stockholm over the weekend. With the revelation of the past secret
talks, his visit is drawing more attention.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been invited by the Swedish Ministry of Foreign
Affairs to attend a ceremony in memory of a secret diplomatic
mission carried out in Stockholm in 1998 which contributed to the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Lindh, on Tuesday, denied recent speculations that Palestine,
Israel and the United States intended to hold a secret summit
sometime before or after the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
