<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Bring Germany to Court on Improper Levy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
here Friday that it would bring Germany to the European Court of
Justice for its levy, which is deemed inappropriate, on German
artists and writers who live outside the country.
</P>
<P>
The levy has violated certain principles contained in EU
Regulation 1408/71, whereby a person should only be subject to the
legislation of a single EU member state for social security
purposes, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, the contribution would finance
health care and pensions for artists and writers who are paid by
publishers or galleries.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the EU's executive body, believes that Germany
should not impose such a levy on German artists and writers who
reside in another EU member state.
</P>
<P>
EU rules say that such people, when they live and work outside
Germany, are not covered by the German social security system.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, when Germany places a levy on their works of art,
these artists and writers have to pay social security both in
their home country and the country where they live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
