<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Possible Explosion Threatens Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam should take more and
quick action if it is to avoid an HIV/AIDS explosion as some
countries have suffered, the Saigon Times Daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily quoted analysts' warning following
shocking figures released recently.
</P>
<P>
Since the first HIV case in Vietnam was discovered in 1990, the
number has grown to 10,268 HIV/AIDS cases, said a report by the
National AIDS Prevention and Fighting Committee.
</P>
<P>
In the tropical diseases center in Ho Chi Minh city, a major
aids hospital in the south, doctors said 280 HIV cases were
treated there in the first eight months of the year, compared to
only 35 cases for the whole of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Patients there come from occupations including civil servants,
police officers, teachers, business people rather than mainly drug
addicts and prostitutes as previously, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
A study of 113 aids deaths shows that 59 died of opportunistic
diseases before they passed to the final aids period.
</P>
<P>
In the sixth ASEAN HIV/AIDS Task Force Meeting held in Hanoi
late October, Vietnam was projected to have between 10,000 and
15,000 aids deaths out of the estimated 135,000 to 160,000 HIV
positive cases by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
