<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Endeavor Blasts Off With Second Element for Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The delayed U.S. space
shuttle Endeavor blasted off before dawn at 3:35 Friday from Cape
Canaveral, Florida, with six astronauts and the U.S.-built Unity
module, the second element for the international space station,
lighting up the dark sky on their way to orbit.
</P>
<P>
Endeavor's mission is to rendezvous with an unmanned Russian
power station Zarya module put into orbit November 20, and to get
the Unity connected with Zarya, forming the basis for the future
assembly of the international space station.
</P>
<P>
During Endeavour's 12-day flight, the astronauts will use the
shuttle robot arm to capture the Russian piece and attach it to
the American component. Then two astronauts will perform three
spacewalks to hook up all the electrical connections and cables
between the two cylinders.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. piece, Unity is a connecting passageway. It is
essentially an aluminum can with big holes where other chambers
eventually will attach. It contains six miles of wiring and more
than 50,000 mechanical pieces.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the alarming in a cockpit, the space shuttle delayed
its take-off 24 hours. Engineers and controllers on the ground
finally determined that the alarm was caused by a momentary low
pressure indication, but that all the shuttle's hydraulic systems
were working properly. However the alarm pose no threat to the
mission.
</P>
<P>
Once a third element--a Russian command module with living
quarters for astronauts--is added in 1999, the station will
become functional. Upon completion, the space station will
stretch 361 feet end to end, and become one of the brightest
objects in the night sky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
