<HEADLINE> Canada's Building Permits Value Down in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The value of building permits
for housing in Canada fell for the second straight month in
October to its lowest level in two years, Statistics Canada said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian municipalities issued about 910 million U.S. dollars
in housing permits in October, down 5.8 percent from September.
</P>
<P>
"It was the lowest level for residential construction
intentions since October 1996," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Activity in Canada's residential sector has been slowing since
the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The decline has been the result of lagging single-family
dwelling construction intentions, which represent about 70 percent
of the residential sector.
</P>
<P>
Housing resales also continued to edge down in October. "This
is consistent with softening consumer confidence and with the
trend and outlook for the general economy," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the non-residential sector, the value of building permits
dropped 10.2 percent to 780 million dollars in October.
</P>
<P>
In October, the overall value of building permits in the
country declined 7.9 percent to about 1.7 billion dollars, the
agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
