<HEADLINE> Primakov: Lack of Confidence Worsens Russia's Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Russian economic recovery
is hindered by the lack of confidence, Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the World Economic Forum in Moscow,
Primakov said a total loss of confidence is the biggest danger
for Russia's reforms.
</P>
<P>
Poorly planned imports, the overvalued ruble, and high tax
policies strangled producers in Russia and deepened the crisis,
in addition to the ineffective banking and government systems, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The premier also said the moratorium imposed on August 17 on
the payments due on government securities destroyed investors'
confidence in Russia's government and commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Refuting a claim that the government would ban the circulation
of the U.S. dollar and call for an end to importation, Primakov
said, "This has not been done, and will not be done."
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors' interests will not be ignored, but we will
continue to give priority to direct investments in the real
production sectors rather than the short-term programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia will continue to expand relations with
international financial organizations but will base relations on
its own interests and circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Referring to privatization, the premier said that the
privatization process is not and will not be reversed." But the
previous governments' privatization programs have been marred "by
some contradictions and distortions."
</P>
<P>
There will be no overall nationalization, but there will be
state regulation. There will be no redistribution of property, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov warned at the meeting that the country's crisis could
become permanent if Russia continued the previous economic
policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
