<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Edges Down to 8.0 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Canada's jobless rate edged down
0.1 percentage points to 8.0 percent in November, Statistics
Canada said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The job gain pushed the overall employment rate up to 60.3
percent in November, the first time since 1991 that the rate has
been above 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
In November, employment rose by an estimated 103,000, bringing
gains so far this year to 425,000, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the strong gain in employment in November, the number of
unemployed was little changed due to an increase in labor force
participation," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the increase in employment in the month was in
full-time work. So far, the full-time jobs have increased by
302,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
Part-time jobs rose by 29,000 in November, offsetting the
decline in the previous month. Since December 1997, part-time jobs
have risen by 123,000. 
</P>
