<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Warns Garbage Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Science and
Technology Zhu Lilan said today that garbage disposal has become a
pressing issue in China's environmental protection campaign.
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, Chinese cities disposed 100 million tons of garbage,
and the figure is expected to hit 150 million tons in the year
2000," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, every Chinese living in cities produced 440 kg
garbage annually, according to Zhu, adding that they have polluted
soil, underground water and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
She said that Chinese are still using "primitive methods" to
dispose garbage. "They simply put garbage in the open air or cover
them up with earth," she said.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 Chinese cities are floating in a sea of garbage
weighing 6 billion tons, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
To change the situation, the whole nation should be aware that
garbage is valuable and they can be converted into useful materials,
such as fertilizer and energy.
</P>
<P>
Zhu suggested that advanced foreign methods be introduced in
dealing with the problem. Garbage must be collected in a
scientific way, and government will make policies in this respect,
she said.
</P>
<P>
She urged departments and companies to develop garbage disposal
technology, and build a sound management system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
