<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges Political Parties to Have Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
Friday urged all political parties in Zambia to promote the
political culture of dialog.
</P>
<P>
Chairing an inter-party talks focusing on Zambia's political
problems such as constitutional changes and electoral process
here, Chiluba asked the ruling and opposition parties not to
blame each other but engage seriously in dialog to find out means
to resolve the country's problems and difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"I realize this is not the place and time for us to try and
push on blames. This is no time to blame anyone," said the
president who was seen as a "neutral person" to chair the talks
that were abandoned in 1992 and resumed late this year.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted that after the abandonment of the process of the
political dialog, Zambia's political climate got very
contaminated and polluted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, very few political parties were ready to listen
to each other and "there were charges and counter-charges,
allegations and counter-allegations," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He called on all political parties to decide deliberately and
seriously to engage in dialog.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba attached great importance to the meeting, saying it
demonstrated "our faith and confidence in ourselves" and spoke
volumes for "our willingness and readiness" to resolve Zambia's
problems and difficulties as a nation.
</P>
<P>
The eloquent leader pinned his hope on the meeting and asked
all parties to do their best for the nation.
</P>
<P>
"I believe together we can create a climate, together we can
create an environment, together we can create an atmosphere, in
which politics will be healthy and sound, in which politics will
be the business of distributing the resources to help develop the
country and improve the conditions of the life of our people,"
Chiluba concluded.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party talks attracted 22 political parties including
the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) and the
largest opposition party, the United National Independence Party
(UNIP), led by former president Kenneth Kaunda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
