<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Survey Shows Optimistic Economic Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence in the
European Union (EU) improved in November this year, an EU business
and consumer survey revealed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The improvement was to a large extent the result of a more
optimistic view by consumers on the present and expected economic
situation, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
However, industry managers lowered their production
expectations and the expected number of booked orders. This
contributed to a decline in the industrial confidence indicator in
November, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also pointed out that the indicator is in line with
its long-term average for the euro-zone, which will start to adopt
the euro beginning January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
With the pickup in share prices and improved consumer
confidence, the survey said, the overall economic sentiment
indicator rose in November but is now dropping to a lower level.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the EU Directorate General for
Economic and Financial Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
