<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong-based Hang Seng
Bank today opened a Beijing representative office, expanding the
bank's network in inland areas to two branches and three
representative offices.
</P>
<P>
Located downtown in the COFCO Plaza, the Beijing representative
office is the first established by the Hang Seng Bank in north
China.
</P>
<P>
Vincent H.C. Cheng, vice chairman and chief executive of the
bank, said at the opening ceremony that this move marks another
milestone in the bank's business development in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"The representative office will be a key strategy point for the
bank to enhance its relationship with the central government as
well as our customers with operations in Beijing," he said. "It
will also complement our network of inland branches and offices as
a liaison with Hong Kong companies seeking to invest and expand in
north China."
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1933, the Hang Seng Bank is a principle member of
the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation Group, and the
second largest locally incorporated bank in Hong Kong, employing a
staff of about 7,800 in its 158 local branches.
</P>
<P>
The bank engages in the financing of infrastructure, hotels,
real estate, and industrial and aircraft projects in inland areas,
as well as other financial activities.
</P>
<P>
The bank has so far set up branches in Guangzhou and Shanghai
and representative offices in Beijing, Shenzhen and Xiamen.
</P>
