<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns of Snail Fever Scourge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Schistosomiasis, also known as
snail fever, if not controlled could develop into a liver and
urinary tract disease and bladder cancer, the World Health
Organization (WHO) warned here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a drive to gain international recognition for the disease
which affects over 200 million people worldwide, over 50 experts
from 22 countries met from December 2-4.
</P>
<P>
The infection, carried by water-borne tiny worms, can cause
severe organ damage if untreated. Victims suffer from liver,
urinary, lung and nervous system disorders.
</P>
<P>
"We have an effective drug, praziquantel, which kills all the
Schistosome species as well as a course of treatment which only
costs between 30 and 40 U.S. cents," said Dr Lorenzo Savioli, head
of WHO's Schistosomiasis and Intestinal Parasites Control Team.
</P>
<P>
"But the numbers of people affected means that buying
sufficient quantities of the drug is beyond what most developing
countries can afford," he added.
</P>
<P>
The schistosomiasis problem has long been associated with the
growth of agriculture in developing countries. A schistosomiasis
problem surfaces each time a dam or other agricultural
developments are undertaken.
</P>
<P>
Experts say there is a direct link between the disease and the
existence of stagnant bodies of water, inadequate water and
sanitation systems.
</P>
<P>
The WHO noted that countries like Brazil, China, Egypt and
Morocco have set examples for exerting easy-to-implement measures
that effectively control and even eliminate schistosomiasis.
</P>
<P>
Scientific evidence has shown that a single dose of
praziquantel can reverse 90 percent of urinary tract lesions in
school children after only six months, while regular treatments,
given to children between the ages of 5-15, can prevent long-term
consequences in adulthood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
