<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Seek Ex-President's Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe has made it clear that he would seek the
extradition of former president Canaan Banana from South Africa,
South African Press Association reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe Thursday told reporters in London, where he is on a
private visit, that Zimbabwe would seek the extradition of
Banana, who was convicted by a Harare court on charges of sodomy
and indecent assaults.
</P>
<P>
Banana fled to Botswana and then to South Africa last week, on
the eve of his conviction. He said there had been political
pressure on the judiciary to convict him.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he had been informed of Banana's escape from the
country and that the former president had talked to both leaders
of Botswana and South Africa, Festus Mogae and Nelson Mandela,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"I talked to President Mogae when I was in France and he
informed me that Banana had not sought asylum in Botswana but had
asked for help with his hotel bills.
</P>
<P>
"I am also aware that he met President N. Mandela and I take
it Mandela will be advising him to return home and face the
music. If South Africa refuses to extradite him, that will not at
all affect my relationship with Mandela," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
"We have an extradition treaty with South Africa to extradite
criminals who have run away from their country, so we can seek
his extradition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's comment contradicted the Zimbabwean government's
earlier statement. A government spokesperson said Harare was
surprised to hear that Banana met Mandela Wednesday, after
Zimbabwean police had issued a warrant for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
A South African presidential spokesman said Thursday that
homosexual acts were not illegal in South Africa, and with South
Africa's strong gay movements, the government had to be careful
to avoid discriminating against Banana.
</P>
<P>
But he said South Africa would cooperate if Zimbabwe went
through the proper channels and approached the authorities for
assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
