<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Tide of Web Advertising Surging in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Qiu Ke, 24, who has a degree in
advertising, resigned from a well-known joint venture in Beijing
one year ago and joined the other pioneers who are exploring
China's Internet advertising market, still a novelty in the
country.
</P>
<P>
To date, Qiu's Blue Process Company has 12 domestic clients for
whom it has created Internet ads. These clients include magazines and
securities companies. "Small as it's now, I'm bullish
about this market," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary statistics, there are now more than 30
companies such as Blue Process in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Stone Rich Sight Company (SRS), which has the
most popular Chinese website in China, has set out to establish
the world's largest Chinese website -- Sina.
</P>
<P>
Deng Hailin, marketing manager of SRS, said that interactivity
is one of the characteristics of the Internet, facilitating
convenient communication between advertisers and
consumers. Advertisers can also accurately calculate the number of
people exposed to their online advertisements.
</P>
<P>
The number of Internet users has rapidly increased over the
past five years. Statistics show that about 80 million computers
were connected with the Internet worldwide by last year, and this
figure is expected to reach 200 million.
</P>
<P>
Advertising on the Internet has also become a booming
commercial activity in Western countries. Experts predict that the
world gross ad investment will reach five billion U.S. dollars in
2000.
</P>
<P>
China's Internet market is closely following the world pace. The
country currently has 1.17 million users, and the figure will
reach two million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
These people are mainly in their twenties and thirties, and are
well-educated and well-paid, said Deng.
</P>
<P>
Most insiders and officials agree that China's Internet ad
market will make rapid progress in the next five years, though it
is not mature now.
</P>
<P>
Deng said that current Internet ad income, which mainly
comes from the information industry, is only less than one percent
that of traditional mass media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
