<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Here are economic briefs from the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Italian "ENSALDO" company has embarked on the
implementation of the Sanaa electricity development project which
will cost 60 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni Vice President Abdo Rabbo Mansour Hadi and the
Minister of Electricity and Water Ali Hameed Sharaf took part
Thursday in the inaugural ceremony of the project at the Sanaa
suburban district of Zahaban.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Sharaf said the project aims at easing
the shortage of electricity in the capital city and improve supply
to towns and villages linked with the national network.
</P>
<P>
The project includes construction of a new power plant using
disel as fuel, with a generating capacity of 70 megawatt, and
expansion of Zahaban power plant to a capacity of 20 megawatt and
of the Omar power plant to a capacity of 180 megawatt.
</P>
<P>
The project is due to be completed within a year.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Iranian companies have signed 25 contracts with Saudi
merchants in the course of the Iranian products exhibition in
Riyadh last month, it was announced by the Iranian Ambassador to
Saudi Arabia Mohamed Reda Nouri.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, the first of its kind, brought about 170
Iranian companies as well as a trade delegation of 400
businessmen, traders and industrialists.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian private sector is looking forward to opening the
Saudi market, increasing trade exchanges and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries increased from 217
million U.S. dollars in 1995 to 271 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The total cost of the rehabilitation of the water
sector and treatment of sewerage throughout Lebanon is estimated
at 1,023 million dollars, besides 200 million dollars for the
construction of dams, it was announced by the adviser to the
Lebanese Minister of Water Resources and Electricity in charge of
water affairs Selim Katafako.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on exploitation of water resources and
treatment of sewerage, he said water shortage reached 73 percent
last year and predicted that it will amount to 285 percent in the
year 2021.
</P>
<P>
Should the rehabilitation projects be implemented, the
situation will improve by 35 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- The second international economic forum will open in
Sanaa Saturday to discuss major projects in the context of a
government plan to attract foreign investments, Friday's Arab
daily Al Hayat reported.
</P>
<P>
The forum will be inaugurated by the Omani Minister of Finance
Ahmed Abdul Nabi Micki. 
</P>
