<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Lead in Men's and Pair's Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Russians showed their ability in
the figure skating again after Friday's competition in the NHK
Trophy tournament in Sapporo, Japan, leading both in the men's
and pairs events.
</P>
<P>
Elena Liashenko of Ukraine took the women's event while Marina
Anissina and Gwendal Feizerat of France were the leaders of the
ice dancing after the day's original dancing at the sixth and
final of the figure skating Champions Series.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Evgeny Plyushchenko took the lead in the men's
singles. In the pairs event Elena Berezhnaya and Anton
Sikharulidze were also in the lead ahead of American sister and
brother, Dannielle Hartsell and Steve Hartsell.
</P>
<P>
Liashenko, 22-year-old winner of Skate Canada women's singles
in July, edged Russian Irina Slutskaya with a flawless
performance of jumps, spins, steps and spirals to receive scores
ranging from 5.4 to 5.6. Slutskaya got 4.9 to 5.4.
</P>
<P>
Uzbekistan's Tatyana Malinina was third, followed by Vanessa
Gusmeroli of France and Japan's Fumie Suguru.
</P>
<P>
With only Elena Sokolova and her Russian compatriot Maria
Butyrskaya definitely qualifying for the Champions Series final
in March, Liashenko is a top contender with 12 points from her
victory in Canada.
</P>
<P>
On the Champions Series circuit, inaugurated three years ago,
skaters are allowed to compete in only three of the six events in
a season, taking two events to tally the points in order to be
able to compete in the series final.
</P>
<P>
For the final, the top six scorers in the men's and women's
singles, pairs and ice dancing events qualify.
</P>
<P>
So far this season, the Russians have won 14 of 20 titles even
without their Olympic champions, Ilia Kulik and Tora Lipinski,
competing.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, Li Chengjiang of China was second,
followed by Japan's Takeshi Honda and Ukraine's Evgeny Pliuta.
</P>
</TEXT>
