<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Sturgeon Released For Scientific Studies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese fish experts today
released hundreds of young Chinese sturgeon into the Minjiang
River in east China's Fujian Province, hoping to gather data for
researches on the rare specie's spawning migration habits.
</P>
<P>
The 400 small fish, 50-100 centimeters long and weighing 2-5
kilograms, were put into the Minjiang River which is believed to
be the sturgeon's main breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon is known as a living fossil as it is one
of the oldest vertebrates in the world. To save it from
extinction, China has placed it under first-class protection and
set up several nature reserves and a breeding center in the city
of Putian in Fujian.
</P>
<P>
The young sturgeons released today came from the breeding
center which has hatched over 3,000 Chinese sturgeons. If this
release proves successful, the center will put more young
sturgeons into the river to boost its number in the wild,
officials at the center said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Snow Closes Shenyang Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Heavy morning snow in the city
of Shenyang in northwest China resulted in the closure of the
Taoxian International Airport.
</P>
<P>
