<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Domestic Debt Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's domestic debt
stock comprising government securities and contingent liabilities
stood at 940.2 billion Shillings or 1.4 billion U.S. Dollars in
late October, up 8.7 percent over the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The increase can be explained by a rise in securities and
contingent liabilities, said a monthly economic review by the
Bank of Tanzania (BoT), the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Government securities which include stocks, bonds, treasury
bills, promissory notes and tax reserve certificates went up by
10.5 percent, due to increases of 18.1 percent and 4.5 percent in
bonds and treasury bills respectively, said the newly published
report.
</P>
<P>
Government bonds rose from 314.7 billion Shillings to 384.5
billion (one U.S. Dollar equals to 660 Shillings), following the
government decision to re-capitalize National Micro-Finance bank
by issuing bonds worth 69.7 billion Shillings to bridge the
bank's financial gap.
</P>
<P>
Treasury bills increased from 110 billion Shillings recorded
at the end of September 1998 to 115.1 billion at the end of
October, said the report.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, according to the report,
contingent liabilities increased by 4.8 percent, from 110.1
billion Shillings at the end of September to 115.5 billion at the
end of October.
</P>
<P>
The increase originated from a 7.5 percent rise in the BoT
revaluation account, following the depreciation of the Tanzanian
Shilling, it said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic debt by creditor category at the end of October
reveals that the BoT and commercial banks are the main holders of
the government securities (stocks and bonds), each accounting for
42.5 percent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Other financial institutions hold 9.9 percent, while other
banks hold 2.5 percent. Official entities hold 1.5 percent and
the rest account for 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said during October, the government issued checks
worth 3.2 billion Shillings to service stocks and bonds. About
500 million Shillings were used to service October dues, while
the rest was used to settle part of long over-due interest
arrears.
</P>
<P>
Despite the substantial payment during the month, interest
arrears continued to surge by 2.1 percent, reaching 120.3 billion
Shillings, compared with 117.8 billion recorded at the end of
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
The October interest on the BoT 25 percent special stock
amounting to 5.2 billion Shillings, largely accounts for the
increase in interest arrears, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
