<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Raises Civil Servants' Retirement Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Service of the
Singapore government Friday announced it has decided to raise the
civil servants' retirement from the age of 60 years to 62 years, a
move deemed in reaction to the worrisome trend of rapid aging of
population in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, the Civil Service, as an employer, will
allow civil servants to carry on working until 62 years old
subject to wage adjustment where applicable.
</P>
<P>
It will also extend the right to pensionable officers if they
wish to.
</P>
<P>
In exchange for the statutory right given to employees to
continue working and earning a regular income, employers will be
given the discretion to adjust wages of employees aged 60 years
and above up to a maximum of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 970 Civil Servants in Singapore, pensionable and
non-pensionable, will turn 60 years old in 1999 and they will be
able to take advantage of the policy to work until 62 years old.
</P>
<P>
In the last decade, residents aged 60 years and over in
Singapore increased from 8.5 percent in 1987 to 10.1 percent in
1997. By the year 2030, there will be one elderly person above 65
years old for every five Singaporeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
