<HEADLINE> Chile's Go-between Offers Pinochet Compromise Deal: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A Chilean politician is in
London to persuade his former leader Augusto Pinochet to accept a
diplomatic compromise which might solve the extradition crisis he
faces, The Daily Telegraph said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that Pablo Longuaira, a member of the
Rightist Independent Democratic Union Party, was trying to arrange
a deal in which Pinochet would be interrogated in Britain by the
Spanish judge seeking his extradition.
</P>
<P>
Longuaira acts as an intermediary for the centre-left Chilean
government to talk directly with the former Chilean leader, the
Paper said.
</P>
<P>
It said Longuaira had also suggested that Pinochet consider
issuing an apology to the victims of his 17-year rule, during
which more than 3,000 people were, alleged by the Spanish judge,
killed or disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph said Longuaira arrived in the British
capital on Wednesday and had seen the 83-year-old Pinochet at his
new luxury rented house southwest of London.
</P>
<P>
General Pinochet regards Longuaira as " a son," the Paper said.
</P>
<P>
But the paper did not say whether the proposed compromise would
be acceptable to Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon, who has requested
Pinochet's extradition.
</P>
<P>
It was also not clear whether such a deal could be agreed by
the British legal system.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Home Secretary Jack Straw must decide by December 11
whether the extradition proceedings against Pinochet can proceed.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was kept under police guard in London on October 16 on
a warrant from Spain. On Tuesday, he moved into a large house in a
wealthy area southwest of London while waiting to hear Straw's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Britain's highest court ruled last month that Pinochet was not
immune from prosecution, opening up the prospect of extradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
