<HEADLINE> Moroccan Leader Calls for Expanded Commercial Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Morocco hopes to develop
commercial ties with China in line with friendly political
relations.
</P>
<P>
Moroccan Prime Minister Abderrahmane Youssoufi made
the remarks to a commercial seminar attended by Chinese and
Moroccan businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
Youssoufi noted that this year marks the 40th anniversary of
diplomatic relations between the two nations, and expressed hope
for expanded cooperation in the economic, trade, industrial,
financial and investment sectors.
</P>
<P>
Morocco hopes to learn from Chinese experience in industrial
and technological development in order to build its economy. He
noted that Morocco welcomes Chinese investors and called for
expanded trade for phosphate and chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 Chinese and Moroccan businesspeople attended the
seminar hosted by the China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade (CCPIT).
</P>
<P>
The China Import-Export Bank and the Moroccan Foreign Trade
Bank signed a two-year agreement calling for the former to provide
the latter with credit totalling 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The China Tea Import and Export Corporation inked an agreement
to export tea to Morocco. The prime minister noted that Moroccans
have developed a fondness for Chinese tea with mint.
</P>
<P>
China and Morocco have witnessed an increasing momentum in
bilateral trade, with the total volume for 1997 rising by 76
percent on the previous year to 160 million U.S. dollars. Trade
for the first nine months this year hit 200 million dollars, up 78
percent from the previous year's period. 
</P>
