<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Disappointed about Macao's 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
here on Friday that China feels disappointed about the Macao
government's decision to incorporate its accumulated fiscal
savings of past years in the 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
"The accumulated fiscal savings are Macao's wealth and should
be turned over to the government of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR), which will lay a foundation for the
future development of Macao," said Han Zhaokang, chief
representative of the Chinese side of the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Liaison Group.
</P>
<P>
Han made the remarks after the four-and-a-half-hour meeting
with his Portuguese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
According to Han Zhaokang, China put forward the point of view
in November of 1997 that China should participate in drawing up
the 1999 budget of the Macao government. In September this year,
the Macao government agreed to hold consultations in this regard
and submitted an outline of the new budget in late November this
year.
</P>
<P>
In the course of consultations, the Chinese side proposed some
opinions on certain points of the budget which might affect the
future SAR government. One major opinion is that the current Macao
government should not put the fiscal savings into the budget.
</P>
<P>
However, the Portuguese Macao government holds that the
incorporation of accumulated savings is aimed at increasing the
"transparency of the budget."
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang noted that the Chinese side does not oppose such a
purpose as long as the Macao government makes a promise that it
will not draw on the savings. But the Macao government would not
like to make the promise.
</P>
<P>
China once again showed a flexible attitude, agreeing that the
Macao government can use an appropriate sum of the savings if it
meets unforeseeable financial difficulties next year. But it
should notify the Chinese side in advance. However, the proposal
was not accepted.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side feels disappointed about this," Han Zhaokang
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the budget issue, the two chief representatives
also discussed the detailed arrangements of the Chinese
government's stationing of troops in the future Macao SAR, pension
for retired civil servants of the Macao government, the official
status of the Portuguese and employment of people from outside
Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
