<HEADLINE> Mandela's Meeting with Banana Denounced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- South African opposition
parties have reacted with outrage to reports that President
Nelson Mandela met fugitive former Zimbabwean president Canaan
Banana at his official residence in Pretoria Tuesday, describing
it as a diplomatic faux pas.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen daily Friday quoted Pan Africanist Congress
spokesman Mike Muendane as saying that Mandela had no right, as a
representative of the South African nation, to resent the country
in that way.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemn the meeting on the basis that Banana is a
fugitive and that his here illegally. The president is therefore
encouraging others to come here illegally and is sending a
message that anyone is welcome in South Africa illegally,"
Muendane said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said South Africa should respect the Zimbabwe's
law. Banana should be deported to Zimbabwe to receive his
sentence on charges of sodomy.
</P>
<P>
Banana, 62, was convicted in absentia by the Harare High Court
last week of using his position as president between 1980 and
1987 to force men, aides, bodyguards and a gardener, to submit to
sex with him. A warrant was issued for his arrest when he fled
the country.
</P>
<P>
Homosexuality is illegal in Zimbabwe but not in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's aide Parks Mankahlana has confirmed the meeting
between Mandela and Banana, saying it had been held in Pretoria
after Banana had requested a private meeting with Mandela.
</P>
<P>
South African foreign affairs spokesman Marco Boni said
Thursday that Mandela's meeting with Banana, which took place at
the knowledge of the Zimbabwean government, did not mean that
South Africa would interfere in international legal processes.
</P>
</TEXT>
