<HEADLINE> Former Zimbabwean President Surfaces in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Fugitive former Zimbabwean
President Canaan Banana has finally surfaced in South Africa and
has already held a private and confidential meeting with South
African President Nelson Mandela, the Daily Herald reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
S. African Presidential Spokesman Parks Mankahlana Thursday
confirmed that Banana had seen Mandela Wednesday in a "private
and confidential" meeting held at the request of Banana.
</P>
<P>
However, Mankahlana gave no further details but said Banana
had not asked for asylum as widely expected. He would not say
whether or not Banana was still in that country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South African government has said it will not
facilitate the capture of Banana unless it is formally approached
by Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a telephone interview with the Herald Thursday,
Mankahlana said Banana, although considered a criminal in
Zimbabwe, had not committed a crime in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The South African government, even if knowing his whereabouts,
had no reason to arrest him unless Zimbabwe formally requested to
do so.
</P>
<P>
Banana fled Zimbabwe last week before the high court convicted
him on 11 counts of sexual offenses committed while he was still
in office.
</P>
<P>
The High Court has issued a warrant for his arrest after the
conviction.
</P>
<P>
Banana is believed to have first gone to Botswana before
entering South Africa.  
</P>
