<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's New Car Sales at 4-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's new
vehicle sales slumped 16.2 percent to 13,884 units in November
year on year, the worst level in four years, dashing hopes for a
speedy recovery in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Sales were down 13 percent compared with the 15,961 units sold
in October, the National Association of Automobile Manufacturers
of South Africa (Naamsa) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented the lowest November month's sales in
the last 12 years, The Star paper Friday quoted Naamsa as saying.
</P>
<P>
The continuing falling sale was mainly a result of
exceptionally high interest rates, which bit into business and
consumer expenditure, Naamsa said. It reflected ongoing weakness
in the economy as a whole, the organization said.
</P>
<P>
South African new car sales have been on a downward trend that
started two years ago, but the pace accelerated this year when
official interest rates were hoisted to a decade-high during a
five-month currency crisis starting from late May.
</P>
<P>
Lending rates have begun to come down gradually, with
commercial banks' prime rate currently at 23 percent, but car
assemblers and dealers said more cuts were needed to revive the
ailing industry.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects for any recovery in new vehicle sales, in the
medium term, would depend on the extent of expected further cuts
in bank lending rates," Naamsa said.
</P>
<P>
The industry anticipated that a modest recovery in new vehicle
sales would only materialize during the second half of 1999, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Naamsa figures showed that in this year to date total new
vehicle sales were 293,447 units, 14.3 percent lower than the
342,419 units achieved in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He warned of further job losses throughout all sectors of the
motor industry, as he believed that the vehicle market was
unlikely to pick up before the third quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that employment in the motor industry fell to
77,500 in 1997 from a peak of 82,100 in 1996. It further dropped
to 73,400 in the first quarter of 1998, according to annualized
figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
