<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Round Anti-Polio Program Launched in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia Friday launched
the second round polio immunization program with an aim to
vaccinate eight million children under the age of five against
polio and measles.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has a plan to eradicate polio by the year 2000 and
the polio eradication campaigns have been conducted twice each
year in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Launching the 3-day second-round immunization campaign, Ali
Abdo, President of Addis Ababa City Administration, said in the
capital that the health service of the national five-year
development program gives priority to the countrywide polio
immunization campaign.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that the major objective of the
national basic health service for children is to prevent and
control diseases which are immediate causes for their deaths.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the immunization campaign which has just been
launched is part and parcel of the basic health program being
conducted to protect children from fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
According to Ali, 92 percent of children under the age of five
years in the capital city were vaccinated against polio in the
last two years and the first round immunization campaign this
year respectively, and 97 percent of children were provided with
vitamin A during the first round of the campaign conducted in
November this year.
</P>
<P>
During the second round campaign, 204,123 children under five
will be vaccinated at 464 vaccination posts in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, N. Nyambi, resident representative
of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), expressed
support for the Ethiopian government in the eradication of polio
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP official said that more than 100 staff of the U.N.
and international volunteer organizations will be part of the
60,000 volunteers mobilized by the Ethiopian Health Ministry in
support of the immunization program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
