<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's External Debt Rises in October: C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's external debt
reached 8,288.2 million U.S. Dollars at the end of October, a 2.5
percent rise from the same period last year, according to a
report by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
A monthly economic review by the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) said
that out of the total amount of external debt, disbursed
outstanding debt was 6,818.8 million U.S. Dollars while committed
undisbursed debt was 1,469.4 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The profile of disbursed outstanding debt by creditor category
reveals that multilateral and bilateral debts are the largest
accounting for 48.7 percent and 44.2 percent of the total debt
respectively, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of total debt owed to commercial sources and
other private creditors is very small, accounting for 4.2 percent
and 2.9 percent respectively, it added.
</P>
<P>
Further, the structure of disbursed outstanding debt by
borrower category shows that the Tanzanian government is the
largest borrower, owing as much as 93.7 percent of the total
debt.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of public corporations and private sector in
the total debt is 2.7 percent and 3.6 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
When classified by economic sectors, the disbursed outstanding
debt reveals that for the period ending October 1998, 24.9
percent of the debt was disbursed in the form of balance of
payments support, while agriculture, transport and
telecommunications received 14.2 percent and 20.4 percent,
respectively, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Energy and mining received 11.9 percent, followed by
industries which absorbed eight percent of the debt. Social
welfare and education, finance and insurance and tourism received
4.2 percent, 2.9 percent and 1.2 percent of the debt,
respectively, while the remaining 12.3 percent of the debt was
absorbed by other sectors, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
The report further said during October 1998 no new loans were
contracted. However, disbursements amounted to 24.2 million
Dollars, while the actual debt service topped to 21.6 million
Dollars. Accordingly, there was a net inflow of 2.6 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The BoT report said implementation of Paris Club V Agreed
Minute up to the end of October 1998 shows that debts worth 371.2
million U.S. Dollars have been canceled, 584.5 million have been
rescheduled and 9.6 million have been deferred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
