<HEADLINE> Philippines to Draw 100 Million Dollars From W.B. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will be able to
draw an initial tranche of 100 million U.S. dollars from a 300
million dollar loan to be extended by the World Bank, an official
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu, the World Bank
loan will be used for the adjustment of the country's banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that the loan, with a floating rate and a 20-year
repayment period and a five-year grace period, will be released in
three tranches up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the World Bank announced that its board has
approved 600 million dollars of loans to the Philippines, which
consist of the 300 million loan, a private enterprise credit
support loan and a rural finance project loan.
</P>
<P>
The other two loans are designed to stimulate private sector
development, create jobs and sustain basic social services for the
country's poor people. 
</P>
