<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Limits Movements for Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian voters are expected to
move freely from their houses to the polling centers but are
restricted to move between states and electoral wards during
December 5 local government elections.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Adamu Muazu, the secretary of the Independent National
Electoral Commission (INEC), was quoted as saying Thursday in
Abuja that the restriction of movement covering inter-state,
intra-local government and electoral wards would last from 8 a.m.
to 2.30 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As part of the security measures, the Nigerian government
announced last week that all borders with neighboring countries
would be closed as from December 4 or Friday to forestall
infiltration of foreigners into the country for voting.
</P>
<P>
INEC Chairman Justice Ephraim Akpata said Thursday that the
commission had suspended indefinitely the conduct of elections in
troubled parts of the country until the restoration of peace and
order in those areas, according to a Daily Times report Friday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the INEC decided not to hold elections in those
areas because "we cannot afford risking the lives of our staff."
</P>
<P>
There is security alert in all states of the west African
country ahead of the December 5 local government elections seen
as a litmus test for General Abdulsalam Abubakar's transition
program, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Lagos State Police Commissioner Sunday Aghedo put his men on a
compulsory 24-hour-duty with effect from Thursday till the
conclusion of Saturday's elections.
</P>
<P>
About 9,000 policemen will be involved in Lagos area to ensure
that the elections are not disrupted, he said, adding that about
2,000 para military men had been enlisted to assist the force
during and after the elections.
</P>
<P>
About 6,996 chairmanship and 79,830 councillorship candidates
of the nine provisionally registered political parties are
expected to participate in the competition for the 774 seats of
local governments in Saturday elections.
</P>
<P>
The Saturday elections will determine which three among the
nine parties will get INEC's final nod. Under Nigeria's
electoral guidelines, political parties would be finally
registered if they scored five percent of total votes of the
local elections in at least 24 out of 36 states in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
