<P>
On the local bourse, the all industrials index added 14.8
points to 4863.0, while the resources index gained 7.6 points to
995.6.
</P>
<P>
Banks were solid, with the banking sector recording a
60.1-point rise to 6146.0.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank lifted 29 cents to 23.79 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank added four cents to 10.22 Australian dollars,
the Commonwealth Bank of Australia jumped 39.2 cents to 22.168
Australian dollars and Westpac bank rose seven cents to 10.05
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP was marked as a standout, gaining
15 cents to 12.15 Australian dollars after reporting crude oil
production from its 50 percent owned Bass Strait assets had
recommenced.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere diversified miner Rio Tinto dropped six cents to
19.59 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index added 11.3 points to 1115.6 on weaker gold
prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 292.60 U.S.
dollars per fine ounce, from 293.25 U.S. dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 299.09 million stocks traded for 621.01
million U.S. dollars, with falling stocks outnumbering rising
stocks 586 to 512 and 431 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
