<HEADLINE> Clinton Said to Help Solve Cyprus Issue Personally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States President
Bill Clinton is ready to become personally involved in the Cyprus
issue in order to achieve a breakthrough in the problem, Cyprus
News Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met Thursday with 16 prominent Greek Americans to
discuss the Cyprus issue. U.S. National Security Advisor Sandy
Berger and State Department Cyprus Coordinator Thomas Miller were
also present at the meeting, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed his intention to become personally involved
in the issue, as was also asked by the Greek Americans at the
meeting, and try to achieve something in the coming two years of
his tenure in office.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in 1974 following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Peace efforts on Cyprus issue have come to a standstill since
the summer of 1997, when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
demanded international recognition of his breakaway state in
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has said it fully backs a fresh effort by the United
Nations resident representative in Cyprus Ann Hercus for a
settlement to the issue and the reduction of tensions on the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
