<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes New Policies on FDI Licensing, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's government has made new
decisions on decentralizing foreign direct investment (FDI)
project licensing and on foreign currency control, official
Vietnam news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The people's committees of provinces and cities under central
government are authorized to grant investment licenses to FDI
projects capitalized below 5 million U.S. dollars each in
accordance with the law on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The new decision to this effect was signed by Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai on December 1.
</P>
<P>
Provinces that had been authorized by the government to grant
licenses to foreign investment projects according to the decisions
made by the prime minister in June, 1997, and in February, 1998,
are not subject to the new decision.
</P>
<P>
The new decision also lists types of FDI projects that
provincial municipal people's committees are not allowed to issue
licenses.
</P>
<P>
They include projects of group a and projects on oil and gas
exploration, exploitation and services, electricity generation,
sea port, airport, highway, and railway construction, cement
production, metallurgy, sugar, alcohol, and cigarette production
and projects located in high-tech industrial zones.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister decided on December 1 that
Vietnam-based organizations must sell all their foreign currency
volume acquired to designated banks immediately when the sum is
transferred to or deposited at their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
The new decision, which will take effect as from the signing
date, will replace articles 1 and 2 of the decision on last
September, which stipulated that Vietnam-based organizations must
sell their foreign currency volume to designated banks within 15
days from the date the sum is transferred to or deposited at their
respective bank accounts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
