<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Officer Calls for Closer Military Ties with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Admiral Joseph Prueher,
commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Command, said here Friday
that the communication between military leaders of China and the
United States is good and improving at a steady pace.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon hosted in his honor by the Asia Society
Hong Kong Center, Prueher said that as part of the "constructive
strategic partnership" called for by both the Chinese and
U.S. presidents, the U.S. Pacific Command aims to promote
military-to-military ties with China.
</P>
<P>
"First, we want to develop and increase understanding by moving
our military relationship beyond the very senior policy, foreign
affairs and protocol channels and into more routine operational
channels," Prueher said.
</P>
<P>
"Second, we want to continue expanding our contacts to bring
younger, more-junior American and Chinese officers together," he
said. "Our experiences with senior PLA (People's Liberation Army)
officers are rewarding and have benefited both countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Prueher said that a secure and stable Asia is a goal that both
China and the United States share and the common goals and
interests between the two countries far outweigh the differences.
</P>
<P>
"We remain optimistic that we can forge a relationship with
China that will meet our mutual interests and work to the benefit
of all nations of the world," Prueher said, adding that it will
come only with increased understanding and clear communication.
</P>
<P>
Prueher arrived in Hong Kong Friday morning as a part of his
official call to several Asian countries and regions. He has been
to Bangkok and Hanoi and will leave Hong Kong for Australia
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
