<HEADLINE> India's Christians Observe Protest Day Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Christians in India observed
a protest day Friday against violence on members of the community.
</P>
<P>
The protest here included a relay prayer, fast and rally
outside Parliament House. They demanded the government take
concrete steps to ensure the security and honor of all minorities,
who, they said, felt highly unsafe and insecure in the prevailing
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Congress, the biggest Opposition in Parliament,
took part in the rally. They said that their party supported the
cause of minorities and urged the BJP-led government to stop
attacks on Christian community in different States.
</P>
<P>
In its memorandum to Lower House Speaker G. C. Balayogi, the
United Christians Forum for Human Rights (UCFHR) claimed that
incidents of violence against Christians this year had been
highest ever in the nation's history and asked the Parliament to
put pressure on the central and State governments to take urgent
action to stop assault on pluralism and religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
The Forum also demanded a white paper with full details of the
violence inflicted on the Christian community, especially in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Rallies were held in State capitals and other places as part of
the protest day by nearly 23 million Christians in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
