<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Former President to be Questioned Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Attorney General
Andi M. Ghalib said here Friday his office will question former
president Soeharto next week.
</P>
<P>
"We will question the former president at the Attorney
General's Office," official Antara News Agency quoted Ghalib as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He did not specify the date and time of the questioning.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib also said he would stick to the presumption of innocence
in questioning Soeharto over the fortune he allegedly amassed
through corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices during his 32
years in power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung said the
possibility of putting former president Soeharto on house arrest
as a follow up to Presidential Instruction is entirely up to the
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
"We will leave it completely to the attorney general to decide
what effective measures should be taken to implement the
presidential instruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Soeharto's attitude toward the investigation of his alleged
hidden wealth, Akbar said the former president is always ready to
be questioned, even without being put on house arrest.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie on Wednesday issued Presidential
Instruction, instructing Attorney General Ghalib to fight
corruption, collusion and nepotistic practices and take judicial
action against Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down on May 21 amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades. He is accused of
corruption and abuse of power during his 32 years in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
