<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners in S.Korea Can Tour Mt. Kumgang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners in South Korea can
tour the Mountain Kumgang in the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) without going through any additional process, South
Korean Ministry of Justice said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners in South Korea will not be required to ask for
permission for reentry or apply for visas before going on the trip
to the Kumgang, said a spokesman of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting on immigration presided over
by Justice Minister Park Sang-cheon.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the minister pledged continued efforts to
improve conditions for foreign residents and to attract more
foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
From next year, the ministry will allow citizens from about 150
countries, with which the nation has concluded no visa agreements,
to stay in South Korea for 30 days without visas, instead of the
current 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The measure is taken under the principle of reciprocity as
these countries allow South Koreans to stay there for up to 30
days without visas.
</P>
<P>
To help further promote exchanges between South Korea and
China, Chinese businessmen who want to make frequent visits to
South Korea will be issued multiple visas, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will no longer make it mandatory for associations
of foreign residents to register with South Korean authorities. It
will also simplify the procedures of issuing residence permits to
foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
