<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- While the Washington conference on robbed Jewish properties
of arts ended on Thursday without taking any legally binding
measure, the U.S. automobile producer Ford was accused by a
Jewish lawyer of collaborating with the German Nazis during World
War II and exploiting prisoners and deportees in its plant in
Cologne, Germany, to provide equipment for the Wehrmacht.
</P>
<P>
-- Israel once again suspended the application of the Wye
Plantation agreements with Palestinians after Palestinian students
protesting Israel's refusal to release their companions attacked two
Jews in Ramallah Wednesday afternoon. Israel released 250
Palestinian prisoners last month in accordance with the Wye
agreement, but 150 of them were prisoners of common laws instead of
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- By lowering their key interests rates to 3 percent, the
central banks of 11 European countries to join the single
currency have in fact hurried the birth of the euro. The measure
by European banks put an end to their dispute with the United
States Federal Reserve and affirmed their unity and capacity to
respond to the economic situation in the world.
</P>
<P>
-- Two young French architects, Marcelo Joulia and Alain Renk,
plan to build temporarily two towers in the shape of the Pyramids
on the Notre Dame Catheral of Paris to celebrate the coming of
the 21st century. By choosing the historic monument as its basis,
the project has the symbolic meaning of going beyond the time and
achieving eternity. 
</P>
