<HEADLINE> Injury Forces Chinese Top Gymnast out of Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese gymnast Lu Yufu has pulled
out of the Bangkok Asian Games becuase of a knee injury he sustained
in practice Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Lu, key member of the 1997 world champion team,
tore his knee ligament in practice on vaulting horse, which is his
leading event and the top chance for gold medal in the Bangkok
Games which starts on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Lu is the leading gymnast in vaulting horse and floor
exercises. He would be China's top hope in the two events," said
Huang Yubing, head coach of the Chinese gymnastics team.
</P>
<P>
China will replace Lu Yufu by Zhao Sheng, who is to fly to
Bangkok from Beijing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, also 20, is waiting for the approval by the Asian Olympic
Council and the Asian Games Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Lu's injury would not lower China's gold target of eight to 10
in the gymnastics competition, in which China has dominated for
the last two Asiads.
</P>
<P>
"Without Lu we'll still win eight to 10 gold medals here," said
Huang. "What I'm really worried about is whether he could recover
in time for the 2000 Sydney Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
Lu jumped to international fame in the East Asian Games last year,
where he captured three gold medals in team, floor exercises and
pommel horse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
