<HEADLINE> China Expects 16 Shooting Golds at Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese marksmen and women are
targeting 16 golds at the Asian Games shooting competitions which
start on Monday, a Chinese official said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that we could win one more gold medal here than
the last Asian Games. That means 16," said Chinese Shooting
Association President Feng Jianzhong.
</P>
<P>
Feng added that China, which won 15 golds, 13 silvers and 10
bronzes at the last Asian Games in Hiroshima, will try to keep its
top position in Asian shooting despite challenges from South
Korea, Japan and former Soviet Union repulics like Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese shooting team is spearheaded by veteran pistol
shooter Wang Yifu and world championships runner-up Wang Xian, and
contains a batch of shooters who obtained good results at World
Cup series.
</P>
<P>
The hot, humid weather here could cause problems for shooters,
who need concentration and composure in competition.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Xu Haifeng, who is in charge of the women's
pistol shooters, gave a confident prediction, saying that his
students would win three of the four golds at stake.
</P>
<P>
Xu told Xinhua his shooters were highly motivated because among
five shooters who came here, four will be fielded and it was still
undecided who would be axed.
</P>
<P>
He rated Japan's Yoko Inada and South Korean Shin Eun-Kyung as
their main rivals.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese squad arrived here on Tuesday but had to wait until
Friday to train in the ranges at Hua Mark Sports Center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
