<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Novelist Depicting Effects Of Rural Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- At the beginning of the
novel "Cang Sheng" (Common Folk), which portrays China's rural
reforms, a man named Ba Fulai who has his label as a landlord
removed is holding a wedding feast for his son and
daughter-in-law, who comes from a poor peasant family.
</P>
<P>
He doesn't expect the village leaders to show up to
congratulate him, and, embracing his son, he says, "Can this be
true?"
</P>
<P>
This description by the well-known novelist Hao Ran does away
with the political distinctions for landlords and their offspring
during the Cultural Revolution (1966-76) that permeated his two
famous novels "Bright Golden Road" and "Bright Sunny Skies".
</P>
<P>
These two novels, published in the '60s and '70s, were Hao
Ran's depictions of the class struggle in people's communes in
rural areas that were some of the few novels permitted during the
Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
But "Cang Sheng", which was published in the 1980s and which
won the China Popular Literature Award in 1990, is a narrative of
the changes in rural areas resulting from the reforms, including
changes in people's attitudes toward the political notion of class.
</P>
<P>
Literary critic Lei Da says that "Cang Sheng" represents the
great changes in rural areas, especially ideological changes, of
people freeing themselves from the ideological shackles of "class
status" and turning to the rural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old Hao Ran now lives in a village in Sanhe County
in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
In late 1978, when he was writing the third part of his novel
"Bright Golden Road", he learned that farmers in the village of
Xiaogang, Fengyang County, Anhui Province, had taken the lead in
breaking up cikkective farmland for household use, a beginning of
the rural reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Novelist Depicting Rural Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"At first I could not accept the changes," Hao Ran says, "I was
rather angry and felt a little loss at what was happening in rural
areas."
</P>
<P>
He says that it was the Communist Party that led workers and
farmers in seizing state power, but the farmers began to correct
the Party's mistakes. "I thought that I could not write about what
was happening in the countryside and that my writing career was
nearly over."
</P>
<P>
In the years after 1978, Hao Ran visited more than 100 counties
in northeastern and northern parts of China, especially villages
that had been sources of stories in his two previous novels.
</P>
<P>
The changes he saw made him aware of the actual disasters that
had resulted from the people's communes and how farmers had been
stimulated by the new household contract system, which linked
income to output.
</P>
<P>
During the people's commune period of 1958 to 1978, about 400
million farmers were living below the poverty line, but now the
number of poor in rural areas has been cut to 30 million, he says.
</P>
<P>
Having been encouraged by the enthusiasm of farmers he saw, Hao
Ram resumed writing about farmers, and their sorrows and awareness
during the reforms.
</P>
<P>
In "Bright Golden Road", when a villager used a spade to scrape
the characters "Build Family Fortune" on the wall of the house of
the village's head Zhang Jinfa, all other villagers applauded
it. But in his new novel, villagers in the mountains near Beijing
are busy making money from local exports, something that was
regarded as a "capitalist tail" during the people's commune period.
</P>
<P>
Hao Ran said that he wants to use his novel to encourage
farmers to become prosperous and to contribute to the reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebel Group Set up Peace Monitoring Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will set up Friday four
monitoring centers tasked to look after truce violations between
government forces and MILF guerrillas in a disputed zone in
Maguindanao, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported that the monitoring centers
will strategically be erected in the Datu Piang-Shariff
Agwak-Talayan complex in Maguindanao Province, the site of recent
fierce fighting between government troopers and MILF rebels.
</P>
<P>
The observation posts will be placed along Crossing Laubani in
Upper Bagan, Talayan; Crossing Salbo in Datu Piang; and Tumaig and
Meta in Shariff Agwak, it said.
</P>
<P>
Teams that will man each post will compose of representatives
of the government and the MILF, civilians and local police
elements.
</P>
<P>
The clashes between the government and MILF forces early this
week in the area killed four soldiers and three rebels and wounded
dozens of combatants from both sides.
</P>
<P>
The conflict also displaced some 500 families who fled their
homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
