<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Investigates Former Government Departments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Less than three days after
Salim Hoss was designated as Lebanon's new prime minister, the
state judicial authority embarked on a probe into accusations
against former government departments and officials.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports in recent days that documents of the
former ministries of finance and the displaced have been removed
or burned, the Daily Star said Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Prosecutor Adnan Addoum ordered security agents Thursday
to investigate these claims which were strongly denied by outgoing
Minister of State for Financial Affairs Fuad Sinyoura, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
Sinyoura, a close ally of the outgoing Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri, said the documents were being removed from the ministry's
old offices to the new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
There are filed copies of all documents in the ministry's
archives, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he had phoned Adnan asking him to clear the air and
expressed his regret for the spread of rumors during the
government's transitional phase.
</P>
<P>
In another judicial development also targetting allies of
Hariri, Beirut public prosecutor Abdullah Bitar has started an
investigation into four former key government officials.
</P>
<P>
They were accused of seizing a real estate property and
annexing it to Solidere, the country's biggest company responsible
for rebuilding war-destroyed Beirut central district. The company
is seen as Hariri's brainchild.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, a billionaire construction tycoon, has been
spearheading during his six-year term under former President Elias
Hrawi a massive reconstruction program to rebuild the country from
the ravages of the 15-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
His sudden departure was believed to have much to do with his
disagreement with the new president, Emile Lahoud, over the
make-up of a new government.
</P>
<P>
As Hariri refused the nomination by Lahoud to resume
premiership, Hoss, a prime critic of Hariri's economic and social
policies was named as the new prime minister Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
