<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation Up in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate
for November jumped to 11.2 percent from 10.2 percent in October
as a result of recent typhoon damage, the National Statistics
Office said in a report Friday.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the inflation increase was caused mainly
by food price hikes.
</P>
<P>
The biggest prices hikes were recorded in typhoon-struck areas,
such as Cagayan Valley, Ilocos and Central Luzon, where supply and
distribution of food commodities were significantly affected.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the average inflation for the first 11
months of this year was 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Socio-economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla said in a
statement that inflation for the entire year is expected to be
within the government target of 9.25-9.75 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
