<HEADLINE> Copper Price Hits 11-Year Low on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Copper price fell to
11-year low Thursday on U.S. market, while the prices of aluminum,
zinc and nickel also slumped on concerns about a shrinking demand
for industrial commodities.
</P>
<P>
At the New York Mercantile Exchange, copper for March delivery
lost 1.45 cents a pound, ending at 68.80 cents, the lowest level
since July 1987.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three-month aluminum ended at 1,264 dollars a ton,
the lowest level since March 1994. Three-month nickel price
dropped by 100 dollars a tonne, hitting 4,030 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"There are ample supplies in some of these commodities markets,
but demand is likely to be lower next year than this year. The
interest rate cuts by European central banks today did little to
stop the slide in commodity prices," said David Rinehimer,
director of commodity research at investment bank Salomon Smith
Barney in New York. 
</P>
