<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Export Sector to register Positive Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's export sector
is poised to chalk up positive growth this year, a reflection of
its continuing export competitiveness despite the currency turmoil
which had placed the sector under stress since 1997, the Ministry
of International Trade and Industry announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
In its 1997/98 report released here, the ministry said the
sector would continue to be the main source of growth for the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented industries are expected to institute
appropriate measures to reduce costs to mitigate against the
negative effects arising from the depreciation of the ringgit to
remain competitive, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that export earnings of major commodities are
expected to register increases in ringgit terms, reflecting the
gains in the exchange rate valuation.
</P>
<P>
In terms of volume, imports are expected to decline, due to
policy measures instituted to reduce imports.
</P>
<P>
However, import value is expected to increase at a higher rate
in 1998 than in 1997, reflecting the increases in the prices of
the merchandise imports,
</P>
<P>
Based on these factors, merchandise exports are expected to
register a strong growth than imports, which would result in a
higher surplus in 1998 than in 1997, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said Malaysia's competitiveness was further heightened by
the country having moved up one notch to become the 18th largest
world exporter in 1997 according to the World Trade Organization
while it maintained its 17th position in terms of imports.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's total merchandise trade last year grew by 12.2
percent to 442.4 billion ringgit (116.421 billion U.S. dollars)
from 394.2 billion ringgit (103.736 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996,
with exports up by 12.4 percent to 221.4 billion ringgit (58.263
billion U.S. dollars) while imports rose by a slightly lesser
margin of 12 percent to 221 billion ringgit (58.157 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
This led Malaysia to chalk up a higher trade surplus of 424
million ringgit (111.578 million U.S. dollars) from a deficit of
253.7 million ringgit (66.763 million U.S. dollars) in 1996, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The report partly attributed the growth of 12.4 percent in
exports last year from only 6.5 percent in 1996 to the favorable
impact of the ringgit's depreciation on the competitiveness of
local products and the improved global demand for semi-conductors.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's share of world merchandise trade declined marginally
to 1.4 percent in 1997 from 1.5 percent in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia continued to maintain a liberal trading environment
although there were increases in import tariffs on construction
materials, heavy machinery and vehicles, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, the U.S., Japan and the EU together accounted for 73.4
percent of the country's total trade in 1997, a slight decline
from the 73.9 percent share in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Light Truck Outsells Cars in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Trucks outsold cars for the
first time in monthly U.S. vehicle sales in November, according to
results released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
November light truck sales for the industry, including pickup
trucks, mini-vans and sport utilities, grew 4.5 percent to 582,927,
giving them 51 percent of the market. Cars fell 0.3 percent to
562,190.
</P>
<P>
"We have forecast continuing growth in the entire light truck
market," said David Cole, director of the University of Michigan's
automotive transportation studies office.
</P>
<P>
Studies show the continuing rise in truck sales has been driven by
a robust economy, low gasoline prices and Americans' growing demand
for the roominess and increasingly car-like luxury of big
sports-utility vehicles and pickups.
</P>
<P>
However, for the whole year, cars still occupy 52 percent of
the market, while 48 percent held by trucks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said trucks can easily overtake cars on an annual
basis if automakers put incentives on segments such as full-size
sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
Luxury model sport utility vehicles will be the hot sellers
over the next five years, said analysts from J.D. Power
Associates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
