<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Chip Industry Group Details Position in Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A lobbyist group for the
U.S. semiconductor industry has urged individuals and businesses
to contact the manufacturers of finished electronic products to
figure out whether they are Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
In a position paper on the Year 2000 issues released Thursday,
the Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA) headquartered in San
Jose, California, said it is important that people inform
themselves about the Y2K issues and take appropriate steps to
ensure that their electronic systems function properly in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The paper was released when the Year 2000 spotlight turns to
chips embedded in consumer electronics systems and no one can tell
how many of them might fall.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K bug comes from antiquated hardware and software formats
that denote years in two-digit formats in electronic systems. On a
practical level, this means that many electronic products, from
computers to video recorders, may not be able to determine whether
the digits "00" stands for the year 1900 or 2000. The phenomenon
may cause some products to malfunction on January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
With a great deal of effort and expense, these systems can be
repaired or replaced. But most observers agree that the biggest
and most widespread disruption might be caused by embedded systems,
which are used to control, monitor or assist the operation of
equipment, machinery or plants.
</P>
<P>
According to the SIA paper, which provides an overview of the
semiconductor industry's role in addressing Y2K issue, the vast
majority of semiconductors are incapable of generating, comparing
or sorting data information.
</P>
<P>
"In general, semiconductor companies do not design or develop
the software programming for the semiconductors they sell," SIA
said. "In the vast majority of cases, distributors or other
entities create the programming. That is why, in the final
analysis, individuals and businesses will have to contact the
manufacturers of finished electronic products to ascertain whether
those products are Y2K ready."
</P>
<P>
But SIA said that chip companies are conducting extensive
research and evaluation programs to resolve Y2K issues under their
control. At the same time, these companies are working
cooperatively with their suppliers and customers to settle
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa to Recover Quickly: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Sub-Saharan Africa could be
one of the regions in the world which will recover most quickly
from the effects of the current Asian economic crisis, the World
Bank predicts.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank's Global Economic Prospects and the
Developing Countries report for 1998 and 1999, issued Thursday,
Africa will see a two-percent fall in its trade for this year,
mainly because of lower commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
But the bank predicts that next year, Africa should again see
growth rates recover to an average of 3.2 percent, second only to
Asia's growth rates.
</P>
<P>
With many African countries having started putting in place
open and coherent macro-economic programs, recovery should
continue in the next millennium, the bank was quoted by Friday's
Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bank notes that Africa should benefit from the fact that
European demand for African commodity and horticultural products
remains strong.
</P>
<P>
Africa also tends to be excluded from the sharp movements in
currency flows that have so damaged east Asian economies over the
last year, it adds.
</P>
<P>
The bank expects commodity prices to improve worldwide next
year and says that east Africa, in particular, should by then be
recovering from the devastating effects of the El Nino weather
phenomenon, which damaged both the tourism industry and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank cites the below-average growth in Nigeria
and South Africa as the main reason for Sub-Saharan Africa's
growth decline, from around five percent in 1995-96 to 3.5
percent last year and an estimated 2.4 percent this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
