<HEADLINE> Iran Offers to Help Resolve Rome-Ankara Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has announced Tehran's readiness to help resolve the row
between Turkey and Italy over Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the offer upon his return from a visit to Italy,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crisis could be resolved peacefully through
political negotiations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Italy and Turkey have been locked in a dispute over Ocalan
since he was arrested in Rome on November 12.
</P>
<P>
Turkey asked the Italian government to extradite Ocalan,
leader of the outlawed Kurdish Workers Party (PKK), which has been
fighting for independence in southeastern Turkey in the past 14
years.
</P>
<P>
But Rome refused the request, citing its constitution forbading
extradition of a suspect to any country where the death penalty is
applied.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Tehran-Rome ties, Kharrazi said that both Iran
and Italy voiced readiness to further promote political, economic
and cultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi hoped for further expansion of relations with Italy,
one of the big trade partners of Iran. 
</P>
