<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slow Clearance Costs SADC Much </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Delays in clearing commercial
traffic and cargo at border entry points cost member countries of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) 60 million U.S.
Dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
A number of deficiencies in both infrastructural, structural
administrative and operational arrangements at borders in the
region are responsible for this cost, according to Southern
African Transport and Communications Commission (SATCC).
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted SATCC working group member
Heather Chalcraft as saying that poor infrastructure at the
borders, unharmonized customs classification system, excessive
paperwork in customs clearance, poor communication between
customs and clearing agencies are among the bottlenecks
identified at border entry points.
</P>
<P>
She said some of the recommendations made by SATCC like the
single document customs clearing facility is already being
implemented in some member countries.
</P>
<P>
The costs incurred in the SADC economies arose from the
inter-connection in commercial transactions between manufactures,
transporters, industries wholesalers and all stake holders in
commerce.
</P>
<P>
The SATCC has recommended border entry points be run by the
private sector to improve efficiency, she said.
</P>
<P>
Chalcraft said that SATCC holds that if private concerns are
to run border entry points in terms of providing facilities
amenities and general administration they will be run much more
efficiently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0210 </DOCNO>
