<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cambodian Economy Hard Hit by Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The formation of Cambodia's
new coalition government led by sole Prime Minister Hun Sen is a
good news for the whole country, especially for its battered
economy.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held its National Assembly election on July 26. The
three major political parties -- the ruling Cambodian People's
Party (CPP) led by then second prime minister Hun Sen, FUNCINPEC
party headed by Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy's self-named
opposition party -- won all 122 assembly seats.
</P>
<P>
As none of the three parties gained two-thirds of the seats
necessary to form a new government on its own, the CPP, the first
major party winning 64 seats, must align with another party or the
other two parties to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
But FUNCINPEC and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) rejected the outcome
of the election, saying the CPP won it through fraud and
intimidation. This led to a political deadlock for four months.
</P>
<P>
The protracted political uncertainty and the impact of the
regional financial crisis since July last year have made the
economic situation worse, with consumer spending down, prices of
basic goods surging and everyone from vendors to garbage
scavengers struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
Particularly worrying was the continuos rise in prices and the
devaluation of the riel, of which the exchange rate against the
U.S. dollar has fallen in the past 18 months from 1/2500 to
1/3900.
</P>
<P>
International aid which accounts for about half of the
government's revenue decreased sharply. And investment is
continuing to slump with investors either losing their confidence
or taking a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
The government's inability to control corruption resulted in
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) canceling its loans.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry, which is a main source of revenues of the
country, was greatly hit. For the first seven months of 1998, the
number of tourist arrivals reached only 121,000, decreasing by
32.1 percent compared to the same period last year. Hotel
occupancy rates hovered at between 10 and 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between 1993 and 1996, Cambodia's economic growth averaged six
percent, but the growth dropped to just two percent in 1997 and it
will not reach three percent this year, according to the Asian
Development Bank (ADB).
</P>
<P>
Economic recession and political instability also caused a
series of social issues. People's living standard continues to
drop. So far, nearly 40 percent of Cambodian citizens still live
in poverty, and more than half of those are not getting enough
food to eat.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1999 will be a crucial year for Hun Sen's new
government to deliver its promise to build an "economic
government."
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's economic recovery will face a lot of difficulties
and challenges.
</P>
<P>
First of all, although there are some indications that
investors will be interested in spending money in a stable
Cambodia, it is unlikely that they will pour in cash overnight.
Prior to 1997, most investors were from Singapore, Malaysia and
Thailand -- countries now are struggling with their own economic
woes.
</P>
<P>
Some Analysts even said Cambodia has lost its traditional
competitive advantages in labor costs because the depreciation of
regional currencies has made other countries' labor costs much
cheaper than those in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, international banking institutions such as ADB, IMF
and the World Bank might not put their top priority on Cambodia.
Instead they might give more loans to South Korea, Malaysia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, to attract investment, the new government has to make
economic and administrative reforms to ensure that people don't
turn to corruption as a way to make a living.
</P>
<P>
But, many economists are optimistic about Cambodia's economic
recovery. They listed some advantages, such as the dollarized
economy, relatively not very bad inflation for a developing
economy and the maintaining of macroeconomic stability.
</P>
<P>
As new Prime Minister Hun Sen said on October 22 that "the
important issue is to give a strong and fresh impetus to the
economic development."
</P>
<P>
"These serious requests demand a reform process. In fact we
cannot achieve everything in a day, but if we idle away and wait,
it means death," said Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
He said, "both the government and the opposition must put the
national interest, social stability and people's livelihood above
all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
