<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Flash Card Market to Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Driven by the surging
digital camera market, flash card shipments will increase at a
compound annual growth rate of 69 percent worldwide between 1997
and 2000, according to a market analysis released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The International Data Corporation (IDC), a U.S. market
analysis firm, estimated the flash card market would increase from
221 million U.S. dollars in 1997 to over one billion dollars in
2002, when over 40 million cards would be shipped worldwide.
</P>
<P>
In addition to digital cameras, according to the IDC study, key
drivers for the growth in the flash card market include
networking, smart hand-held and other consumer devices requiring
removable memory.
</P>
<P>
Flash cards are so named because they use flash memory chip,
which holds its content without power. Less expensive and more
dense, flash memory must be erased and written in fixed blocks,
typically ranging from 512 bytes up to 256 KB.
</P>
<P>
The IDC said that worldwide cost per mother-board (MB), the main
printed circuit board in an electronic device, will help drive
card unit growth. Research shows that there has been a 50 percent
reduction in cost per MB within the flash card industry from 1997
to 1998. IDC believes that prices will still drop quickly,
leveling out to less than one dollar per MB by the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
