<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lufthansa, S. Africa Airways to Double Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Lufthansa Cargo and South
African Airways (SAA) will more than double their freight
capacity between Nairobi and Europe next week when they add three
cargo flights to their shared schedule.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be flying six frequencies every week, with the
exception of Monday," Nicolas Danton, regional sales manager for
Lufthansa Cargo, was quoted by Friday's East African Standard
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are starting from week 50 with a full program which will
begin Tuesday (December 8)," he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Danton said the extra capacity was required to handle strong
demand from exporters of Kenya perishables through the European
winter.
</P>
<P>
In an ongoing joint venture, Lufthansa Cargo and SAA will add
three Boeing 747 freighter services to the three McDonnell
Douglas MD-11F flights they already share between Johannesburg,
Nairobi and Germany each week.
</P>
<P>
Danton said Lufthansa Cargo, which sells the north-bound cargo
capacity from Nairobi, will offer 250 tons weekly to Europe from
Kenya until the end of the winter season.
</P>
<P>
Cargo uplifted from Nairobi will account for about half of
each aircraft's capacity, he said, with the rest filled from
Johannesburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater Erosion Control Efforts Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Provinces and autonomous
regions on the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze and
Yellow rivers have been instructed to accelerate efforts to
curb serious soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, today called for strengthened water and soil
efforts in the areas to reduce the adverse effects of heavy
flooding, landslides and various other natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Heavy summer flooding along the Yangtze, Songhua and Nenjiang
rivers exacerbated erosion problems and heightened the concern of
people across the nation.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee dispatched two law-enforcement groups
to the areas in October and November to inspect water and soil
conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
Buhe addressed related problems during a meeting held to review
reports of water and soil conservation inspections carried out in
Sichuan Province which is located on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, and both
Shaanxi and Shanxi provinces along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that effective water and oil conservation is
extremely important for maintaining sustainable economic and
social development.
</P>
<P>
The NPC confirmed the achievements related areas have recorded
in afforestation and in both water and soil conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Buhe pointed out that China still faces an arduous task in
curbing soil erosion in the two river valleys in spite of a number
of erosion control projects. He also noted major construction
projects and the extensive development of resources have created
new erosion problems.
</P>
<P>
The NPC leader called on local governments at various levels to
strictly implement laws and regulations governing water and soil
conservation, and noted that people's congresses at all levels
should strengthen supervision efforts.
</P>
<P>
He said Sichuan has taken the lead in introducing a ban on
logging in natural forests, and noted that provinces and
autonomous regions on the Loess Plateau should immediately follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
He also called increased afforestation efforts in the areas and
the introduction of additional major projects to control erosion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
