<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corruption Causes Heavy Loss to Bangladesh Airline: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Corruption and irregularities
have caused losses worth 1,049.5 million taka (21.64 million U.S.
dollars) to Bangladesh's national airline, Bangladesh Biman, a
press report here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A special audit into its 1995-96 accounts also showed that the
airline had a large amount of fund stuck up in bad debt with
agents, the front-paged report in The Daily Star newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Irregular handling of business with sales agents was the
principal cause behind Biman's bad debt, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Instances of mismanagement included credit facility exceeding
agents' bank guarantee, issuance of credit installment without
adjustment of earlier sales accounts and non-payment of money
collected form the sale of tickets by the agents.
</P>
<P>
Biman also suffered losses through unauthorized payment of
incentive commissions, unplanned expenditure for sales promotion,
transport of Bangladeshi deported form abroad, faulty purchasing
processes and excess payment of overtime allowances, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 157 sales agents operated with a bank guarantee of
15 million taka (309,000 dollars), much less than the necessary
133.5 million (2.75 million dollars), which had helped create the
huge debt problem, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The audit found that 11 sales agents owed the airline about
29.6 million taka (610,000 dollars), and 20 travel agents owed
Biman 29.9 million taka (616,000 dollars) which had remained
outstanding for long.
</P>
<P>
Biman suffered a loss of 39.7 million taka (819,000 dollars)
from shipment of Bangladeshi deportees, 243.2 million taka (5.01
million dollars) due to failure to collect outstanding dues, and
overtime allowances accounted for 89.2 million taka (1.84 million
dollars) losses for the airline.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring of Biman's flight operation plan was one way to
reduce its losses, the report said, suggesting the cancellation of
Biman flights on Dhaka-London, Dhaka-New York and Dhaka-Tokyo
routes, which incurred losses of 914.3 million taka (18.85 million
dollars) between 1994 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
