<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Cagers Hungary for Asiad Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Without the Asia top center
Zheng Haixia, the Chinese women basketball team, reshuffled in
March of the year, has set an ambitious aim of re-taking the gold
medal after 12 years in the coming 13th Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"We have paid keen attention to every opponent, and we still
fix our goal on the gold despite a string of unfavourable
factors," said Ma Yuenan on Thursday who took the helm of the
squad in last December.
</P>
<P>
Coach Ma was cornered to field in a squad with 10 debutants for
the Asian Games while chief rivals South Korea and Japan are
steady in their inflow of new bloods into the national squads.
</P>
<P>
For China, with the exception of Zheng Dongmei and Ma Zhongqing
who competed in the last Asian Games, the lack of experiences is
nevertheless their Achilles tendon.
</P>
<P>
"But we are ready to fight against every opponent as we have
our upperhands in height and stamina with an average height of
1.82 meters and an average age of 23.18," said 1.97-meter center
Wang Fuying.
</P>
<P>
In a warmup for the Asian Games, the Chinese cagers have gone
through a 65-day intensive training by playing 18 games on and off
their soils.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women have achieved their glory by finishing second
both in the 1992 Olympic Games and the 1993 World Championships
when the 2.04-meter Zheng was voted the best center of the world.
</P>
<P>
After their glory in the 1986 Seoul Games, the Chinese squad
was blocked twice by South Korea to repeat its Asiad feat, first
in the final in Beijing, then in the semifinal in Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
Zheng who was suffering injuries to her back and waist, jumped
to the international fame in the 1985 World Championships, and
became the first Asian woman cager to play in the WNBA when she
was enrolled by the Los Angeles Sparks in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
