<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dispute Between Dhaka, WB Delays Air Quality Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A dispute between Bangladesh and
the World Bank (WB) has delayed the implementation of a WB-funded
air quality management project in the South Asian country's
capital city.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose when the Department of Environment under the
Ministry of Forest and Environment demanded 250,000 U.S. dollars
to purchase land for setting up air quality controlling check
posts in the city while the WB disagreed, The Bangladesh Observer
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
To get the financial assistance the WB approved earlier this
year, the Environment Department would have to prepare a project
implementation unit and to appoint a project director, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The department needed to buy land or arrange lease from the
Dhaka City Corporation to set up air quality monitoring equipment,
the report quoted a department source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The WB said there was no need of buying land to set up premises
for the 6.3 million-dollar air controlling program and the check
post would likely to be at Manik Mia Avenue which was already
monitoring the vehicles and conducting a mobile court in the city
for the last one month.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, 20 check posts would be set up in phases
across the city to monitor air quality and vehicle emissions.
</P>
<P>
The Environment Department launched a mobile court late October
and monitored nearly 2,700 vehicles during the last one month. Of
the vehicles, more than 1,700 were cautioned by warning stickers,
nearly 780 were caught with defects and the rest were fined.
</P>
<P>
The department started a similar drive in June this year but
was closed at the end of July because of lack of fund and
cooperation of the police.
</P>
<P>
To control the vehicular air pollution, the major source of air
pollution in Dhaka, the WB and the Environment Department have
proposed to phase out leaded petrol by 1999, ban new licenses and
route permits for two-stroke engines, and introduce compressed
natural gas for vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
