<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Eyes 4-5 Table Tennis Golds in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Without veterans Deng Yaping
and Wang Tao, China lowered their goal to four or five gold medals
in the 13th Asian Games' table tennis competitions.
</P>
<P>
China sent five men and as many women table tennis players to
Bangkok, where they are set to meet tough challenge from South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The men's team are led by world No. 2 and Olympic champion Liu
Guoliang and No. 3 Kong Linghui, both world champion and World Cup
winner in 1995. The other three are Wang Liqin, Yan Sen and Zhang
Yong.
</P>
<P>
World No. 2 Li Ju, and No. 3 and twice World Cup winner Wang
Nan will spearhead the women's squad which also include world
No. 4 Yang Ying, No. 7 Wu Na and rising star Zhang Yining.
</P>
<P>
"We aim for four or five gold medals here because the games
rules allow only two players from the same delegation in every
event," said China head coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Deng Yaping has opted out of the Asian Games to
concentrate on her study at Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Olympic silver medalist Wang Tao, who holds a nearly perfect
record against South Koreans, was dropped from the team because
of lack of form.
</P>
<P>
With unmatchable depth and pool of talents, China is certain to
win the women's singles title and two team events.
</P>
<P>
In men's singles, only South Korean Kim Taek Soo is able to
shake Chinese dominance.
</P>
<P>
The only Chinese who holds Kim in awe is Wang Tao, who has only
lost one match to the South Korean in dozens of their encounters
in a decade.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 world championships, Kim beat Wang in the
quarter-finals but he was thrown out of competition because his bat
contained a speed-and-spin-enhancing glue banned by the
Interntional Table Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
With Wang Tao in semi-retirement, Kim fears no one.
</P>
<P>
Kong linghui, who fell a prey to Kim in the Atlanta Olympic
Games in 1996, has never won an easy match against the tenacious
South Korean. Their matches usually ended in 3-2, either in favor
of Kong or Kim.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guoliang has lost two matches this year to Kim, who, in
their latest clash, routed the Chinese fast-attacker 3-1 en route
to winning the World Cup silver medal in October.
</P>
<P>
"Kim Taek Soo is very aggressive and he remains China's top
threat," said head coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
China's strongest opponents in doubles events will also come
from South Korea, who claimed to win at least one gold from
these events.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the same par with South Koreans in women's doubles
and a little better in mixed and men's doubles," said Cai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
