<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, December 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's corporate sector owes foreign creditors
41.7 billion U.S. dollars, Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said.
</P>
<P>
Supachai, also Commerce Minister, said in remarks published by
Friday's Bangkok Post that he was confident 11 bills supporting
financial and economic reform would be passed by parliament before
 the end of the first quarter of next year. (Thailand-Debt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's net foreign exchange reserves declined
by 1.8 million U.S. dollars to 14.21 billion U.S. dollars in the
week which ended on November 30, the Jakarta Post Friday quoted a
statement from Bank Indonesia as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The decline was due mainly to repayment of part of the
government's overseas debt, the statement said.
(Indonesia-Reserves)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The 15 European Union (EU) countries have increased
more imports from 11 Asian countries and areas. EU's trade
deficit with the Asia region rose last year to 31 billion ECUs
(some 34 billion U.S. dollars) from 16.2 billion ECUs (17.8 U.S.
dollars) in 1996, according to EU's statistics available here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 11 Asian countries and areas are China, Japan, South Korea,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Brunei
and Vietnam, as well as China' Hong Kong. They have been denoted
as Asia 11 since they participated in the Asia-Europe Meeting
(ASEM) in London in April this year, the statistics report said.
(EU-Asia-Trade Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) said Thursday that it is necessary to establish
rules for international investment.
</P>
<P>
But senior OECD officials failed to agree at an informal
meeting Thursday in Paris to resume talks on a Multilateral
Agreement on Investment (MAI), which went into a deadlock last
December because of a boycott by France. (OECD-Int'l Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's trade surplus is expected to fall to 28
billion U.S. dollars in 1999 from an estimated 40 billion this
year due to a rise of imports, the Korea International Trade
Association said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a report on the 1999 trade outlook, the association said
increased export of electronics products and automobiles will
depend on demand from developing countries and could be offset by
a slowdown of the U.S. economy, pushing up export volume by a mere
0.4 percent to 133 billion dollars next year. (SKorea-Trade
Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai government officials have called for special
emphasis on trade liberalization to strengthen the country's
economy and protect export.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi Wednesday said
that promoting liberalization is a goal that could not be achieved
 without the support of overseas capital, more sophisticated
technology and wider access to markets. (Thailand-Trade
Liberalization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's economy showed robust growth in the third
quarter, rising by 2.8 percent on an annual basis and up 0.9
percent over the second quarter, the German Federal Statistics
Office announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The office's report also said the gain in eastern Germany was
1.7 percent lower than that of western Germany's 2.9 percent.
(Germany-Economy-Growth) 
</P>
