<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dong Ethnic Group Entering Outside World (1) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series-Part 5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: What follows is
the fifth in a series of stories on the rapidly-changing lives and
culture of the Zhuang, Dong, Miao, Yao, and seven other main
ethnic groups in west China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
which will mark its 40th anniversary on December 11:
</P>
<P>
Shi Canhui, a member of the Dong ethnic group, picks up a leaf
and puts it to his lips and the whistle-like music reverberates
off the walls of the Guishan Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
This "leaf music" helped win the young man his bride, as well a
job in the Guishan, one of the most luxurious hotels in the city
of Guilin, a well-known tourist city of Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the songs and dances that he, his wife, and other
members of his ethnic group perform are part of a regular program
that provides entertainment for guests at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
Shi is from mountainous Sanjiang Dong Autonomous County, which
is home to 340,000 Dong people, who are members of one of 18 large
ethnic groups in China, each with a population of more than one
million.
</P>
<P>
In the past, most of the Dong people led isolated lives up in
the mountains or in remote villages. They call themselves the
"jiang", meaning "a place covered with tree leaves".
</P>
<P>
Shi's ancestors never even dreamed of leaving the mountains,
and as late as the early 1950s, there was not even a road into the
self-supporting mountainous county.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980s, however, great changes have taken place in
Sanjiang, with new highways increasing the movement of rural
laborers to cities and television and telephone lines that reached
out-of-the-way Dong villages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Title Hopeful Pulls out of Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese runner Toshinari
Takaoka, who won the 5,000 and 10,000 meters titles in the
Hiroshima Asian Games, has withdrawn from the 13th Asiad because
of a right thigh muscle injury, Japanese officals said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has pinned hope on the 28-year-old Takaoka and champion
sprinter Koji Ito to help them better their haul of five
athletics gold medals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Tokaoka holds the Games records for both his distances with
times of 13:38.37 and 28:15:48.
</P>
<P>
Team officals said his injury would not recover in time for
the start of the athletics competitions next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dong Ethnic Group (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Traditional Dong architecture is also changing. In the past,
the Dong built wooden houses on the mountainside. Across the river
in front of the village, there was usually a covered bridge to
shield people from the wind and the rain. Chengyang Wind and Rain
Bridge, which is one of the four most famous bridges in China, is
in Sanjiang.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shanren, an experienced carpenter and Chengyang's builder,
said that nowadays few people ask him to build wooden homes,
because with more money available, they prefer a more solid,
fireproof brick home.
</P>
<P>
But, even though these skilled carpenters are needed less in
these parts locally, they are welcome in the cities, where
interior remodelling is a popular thing. And Yang has already
helped build four Wind and Rain bridges in tourist zones in
Beijing and Jiangsu. He has also been invited to use the ethnic
style for buildings in the United States and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Dong's songs and dances for festivals or romances in the
past have become a new source of income in the tourism
business. The county and townships all have their own troupes and
some local artists have been invited to perform in the cities of
Nanning, the regional capital, and Guilin.
</P>
<P>
Shi Canhui said that over 100 people from his village have
found jobs in cities in tourism, construction, or roadwork.
</P>
<P>
At Linxi Primary School, up in the mountains, a group of girls
in one of the four classes for girls in Sanjiang County, in
colorful ethnic costumes, can be seen using computers.
</P>
<P>
"The classes are designed to give special training to Dong
girls who are generally quite shy by nature," said Yang Shunfeng,
the headmaster. One of them said that she dreamed of becoming a
capable career woman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's GDP Expected to Drop in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's gross domestic
product (GDP) will fall by 1.4 percent in 1999, according to a
forecast by the Brazilian National Association of Open Markets
Institution (Andima), press reports said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's unemployment rate could go up to 9.9 percent next
year, said the national economic research body.
</P>
<P>
Andima predicted the inflation rate would be 0.6 percent
compared with the two percent forecast by the Institute of
Economic Investigations Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The foundation claimed that the country's primary public
deficit, excluding payment of interests, would balance at the end
of this year and become a surplus equal to 2.2 percent of the GDP
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the payment of interests, the public
accounts nominal deficit will fall to 7.6 percent of the GDP at
the close of 1998, and to 5.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the public debt will continue to rise from the 39.5
percent of the GDP of this year to 43.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Most Andima analysts foresee a possible devaluation of the
real, the Brazilian currency, of seven to eight percent in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
