<HEADLINE> HK Snooker Ace Confident in Asiad Debutant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Snooker star Marco Fu Ka-chun
of Hong Kong, China said he was confident of standing upon the
podium at the snooker competition in the 13th Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
With his silver-medal performance in his professional debut at
the British Grand Prix in October, Fu vowed on Thursday to put up
his best performance in the Bangkok Games to award Hong Kong,
China a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Fu is tipped as one of the best hopefuls for a gold medal for
Hong Kong, China, that has not won any gold medal at the Asian
Games ever since its bowling victory in the 1988 Seoul Games.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Fu finished runner-up after losing 9-2 to world
number nine Stephen Lee in the title clash at the Preston event
where he became the first ever Asian player to reach the final.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Fu attained the feat of becoming the world's first
ever player to win both the Amateur World Championships and
under-21 Youth World Championships in a same year.
</P>
<P>
Fu said he does not see any particular player as his major
opponent but admitted local hero 15th-ranked James Wattana, Sam
Chong of Malaysia and Shaukat Ali of Pakistan may pose threats in
his voyage along the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Joining in Hong Kong's Olympic champion woman windsurfer Lee
Lai Shan and star cyclist Wong Kam bo as medal hopefuls, Fu will
compete in three events of the singles, the doubles and the team
competitions in the Bangkok Games, and he was confident of winning
a medal especially from the singles.
</P>
<P>
Fu began his touch of the game at the age of eight, with the
help of one of his father's friends.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Hong Kong Billiard and Snooker Council said that
to further promote the sport, they would propose to set up a
systematic coaching system for up-and-coming players with a
qualified coach probably from overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
