<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Logging Endangers Butterfly Habitat in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Mexican environmentalists
warned Thursday that illegal logging and construction of a
recreation park in the "sanctuaries" of the monarch butterfly
could cause the mass destruction of the species.
</P>
<P>
Mexican poet Homero Aridjis, president of One Hundred Group of
environmentalists, said his organization had called on the federal
government to act against the development and on the local
authorities to respect the ecological site.
</P>
<P>
Aridjis warned that freezing temperatures this week in the
Michoacan forests could kill the butterfly colonies, as happened
in 1992 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 million butterflies died in 1992 and 1995 because of
freezing weather made more acute by the felling of pines in the
months preceding the arrival of the insects.
</P>
<P>
Officials estimated that during the 1980s, 50 percent of the
region was covered in pine forest, but that has shrunk to just 25
percent in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Aridjis, also president of Pen International, a group of
intellectuals from around the world, said the butterfly
sanctuaries were also being threatened by a tourist project.
</P>
<P>
Millions of monarch butterflies fly 3,000 kilometers non-stop
from the south of Canada in a 25-day to escape the northern winter.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government has declared five forest regions of
Michoacan and one in the state of Mexico as sanctuaries -- places
that are an ecological reservation where the butterflies reproduce.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that from 100 million to 140 million insects
will arrive in Mexico and many will die during hibernation, while
50 percent will be mutilated or attacked by natural predators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
