<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Puttalam Cement Factory Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Puttalam Cement
Ltd., the country's largest cement factory, has launched its
biggest expansion program costing 22 million U.S. dollars to meet
the growing demand for cement, the official Daily News said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The program will increase production to one million tons from
the current 450,000 tons and will be completed in 1999, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The expansion is expected to serve the company well since the
construction industry is to post higher growth next year following
a host of incentives offered by the government through the 1999
budget, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The company's Managing Director Manilal Fernando told the paper
that already 15 million dollars had been spent so far on the
expansion program.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, a cooler tower to minimize pollution and a
state-of-the-art vertical mill replacing a roller mill will be set
up, said the report, adding that a modern crab crane has also been
installed at a cost of 900,000 dollars. 
</P>
