<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Presidential candidate of
Panama's ruling Democratic Revolutionary Party Martin Torrijos
said Thursday that Panama-U.S. relations will remain strong in the
next millennium as the two countries tackle common issues.
</P>
<P>
"Relations with the United States are hugely important because
both nations share common interests and joint responsibilities
through a neutrality treaty," said Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a press conference announcing that his
electoral campaign will start in February next year, three months
before the May 2 general election.
</P>
<P>
Torrijos is the son of the late Panamanian leader Omar
Torrijos, who negotiated the 1977 Torrijos-Carter Panama Canal
treaties under which Panama will regain sovereignty of the canal
on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Torrijos said the U.S. will continue to be one of the biggest
users of the canal, after its return to the Panamanian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"We have the desire and the potential to increase the trade
between the two nations, especially with those states whose
economy depends on the transit of their products through the
Panama Canal," he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the importance of maintaining the fight against
international drug trafficking and money laundering, although he
did not mention a stalled project to establish in Panama a
multilateral anti-drug center, negotiated by the present
government and the White House.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a senior U.S. official said at a meeting of
American defence ministers in Colombia that two or three sites
were being considered for the relocation of the U.S. military's
anti-narcotics operations from Howard Air Base in Panama. 
</P>
