<HEADLINE> Thai Trade Exhibition Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A four-day Thai trade
exhibition, sponsored by the Department of Export Promotion of
the Thai Ministry of Commerce in collaboration with its Myanmar
counterpart, is being held here beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, held under the Myanmar-Thai economic
cooperation promotion program, was jointly inaugurated by
visiting Thai Deputy Minister of Commerce Pravich Ratanapian and
Myanmar Commerce Minister Major-General Kyaw Than.
</P>
<P>
The first exhibition of Thailand in Myanmar, aimed at
stimulating trade and investment between the two countries,
displays a wide array of products and services of 93 Thai
prominent manufacturers and exporters.
</P>
<P>
The products and services cover automotive parts and
accessories, pharmaceutical products and medical supplies,
construction materials and hardware, cosmetic, electrical products
and parts, fashion goods and textiles, fishery materials, food,
freight forwarding, furniture, hotel and resort, warehouse,
international education, painting supplies, and stationery.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony, Kyaw Than said more than
80 percent of Myanmar's external trade remain in Asia and the
country attaches great importance to further developing and
strengthening trade relations with Asian countries in general, and
with five neighbors in particular -- Bangladesh, China, India,
Laos and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
On the Myanmar-Thai border, Myanmar has opened three trade
points at Tachilek-Maesai, Myawaddy-Maesod and Kawtoung-Ranong
with one more trade point, the Phaya Thonzu, to be added soon, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Myanmar, which has large stores of natural
resources and 16.5 million active labor force, has brought about a
total volume of foreign investment exceeding 7.8 billion U.S.
dollars up to now with Thailand as the third largest investor next
to Singapore and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Thai investment covers sectors of oil and gas, hotels and
tourism, livestock breeding and fishery, industrial estate and
transport.
</P>
<P>
According to Myanmar official statistics, bilateral trade
including border trade stood at 330 million U.S. dollars in the
1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, up from 289 million
dollars in 1996-97. The balance of trade was in Thailand's favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
