<HEADLINE> Thai Companies Owe Foreigners 41.7 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's corporate sector
owes foreign creditors 41.7 billion U.S. dollars, Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said.
</P>
<P>
Supachai, also Commerce Minister, said in remarks published by
Friday's Bangkok Post that he was confident 11 bills supporting
financial and economic reform would be passed by parliament before
the end of the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the bills, particularly those covering foreign
business, bankruptcy and foreclosures, would be crucial to the
country's recovery from last year's economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
He promised new foreclosure and bankruptcy rules would be
passed by March.
</P>
<P>
Total Thai corporate debt stands at up to 7 trillion baht (194
billion dollars), of which 1.5 trillion baht (41.7 billion
dollars) was owed to foreigners, Supachai said, adding that this
underscored the need for changing the old bills to support
financial and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said the government was
willing to change some details of the bills to get them passed
quickly.
</P>
<P>
"If the passage of the bills is approved by the first quarter
of next year, it would be good for the overall economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Banthoon Lamsam, president of Thai Farmers Bank, said failure
to pass the new legislation would be "disastrous" for the country.
</P>
<P>
"The fate of the economy and the financial system depends on
the passage of these bills," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
