<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Chileans' Daily Life Not Affected by Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Most Chileans think that the
case of their former leader Augusto Pinochet has not affected
everyday life and oppose boycott of British or Spanish goods over
Pinochet's detention, a poll indicated.
</P>
<P>
The poll, published in Thursday's press, was conducted by
Britain-based Market Opinion Research International in 29 Chilean
cities, where 67 percent of the country's population lives.
</P>
<P>
An executive of the corporation said she was amazed at the
result of the poll, as the Pinochet case had aroused shocks in the
Chilean official circles.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,190 respondents, who are above the age of 18, some 71
percent said the case had no impact on their life while 82 percent
were against a boycott of goods from Britain, where Pinochet was
detained, or from Spain, where judiciary has demanded Pinochet's
extradition.
</P>
<P>
Six percent said they were "pleased" with Pinochet's arrest in
London on October 16, five percent felt "regretful" and two
percent "enraged."
</P>
<P>
Only six percent were worried that a military coup might be
triggered by the case and three percent feared that the economy
might be affected. Some 66 percent believed that Chile's
democracy process would not be threatened by the case.
</P>
<P>
The pros tied the cons on the question whether it was proper
for the British authorities to arrest Pinochet, while 63 percent
said Pinochet should take responsibility for his alleged serious
crimes, and 57 percent thought he should face trial.
</P>
<P>
The poll closed on November 24, the day before the highest
court of Britain ruled that Pinochet did not enjoy immunity from
prosecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
