<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Exports Down 11.63 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- India's exports fell sharply
in October this year, registering a decline of 11.63 percent over
the same period last year, official sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Exports in October 1998 stood at 2.59 billion U.S. dollars,
lower than the 2.94 billion dollars recorded in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
At an aggregate level, exports in April-October this year are
estimated at 18.87 billion dollars, 5.08 percent lower than 19.88
billion in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in October this year, however, registered an increase
of 8.06 percent to 2.37 billion dollars over 3.12 billion dollars
in October 1997. Trade deficit for April-October is estimated at
5.79 billion dollars, which is higher than 2.67 billion dollars in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The abysmal export growth is primarily due to a negative growth
of exports in cotton yarn fabrics, ready-made garments,
engineering goods, basic chemicals and hardware electronics goods.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
