<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Cuts Discount Rate to 3.5 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Italy cut its
discount rate from four percent to 3.5 percent Thursday, following
interest rate reductions by Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said that the collective
rate cuts would encourage investments and sustain the momentum for
growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that other euro zone central banks, including
the Spanish, Belgian, Portuguese, Finnish, Irish and Austrian
central banks, all brought their key rates down to three percent
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The across-zone cuts were based on a consensus of economic and
financial assessment at Tuesday's meeting of the euro zone central
banks, according to senior Bank of Italy officials.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts here predicted that before the end of the
year, Italy's rate will come down to three percent, which is the
criterion for entering the single European currency system.
</P>
</TEXT>
