<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Advice on Fate of Israeli Spy Pollard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has asked senior officials to offer recommendations by January 11
on whether convicted Israeli spy Jonathan Pollard should be
granted clemency, a White House official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president will make his decision "in a timely manner" after
receiving the recommendations, National Security Council spokesman
David Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Pollard's release was sought by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu as a last-minute condition in the Mideast peace
agreement at Wye River Plantation on Maryland's Eastern Shore in
October.
</P>
<P>
The issue threw the talks off track until Clinton promised to
take a fresh look at clemency for Pollard.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said Clinton "never made a determination to release Mr.
Pollard. He consulted with his advisers at Wye, came to the
conclusion this was not something he was prepared to do at Wye and
he made his own decision to take a fresh look at this case and to
consult all the appropriate agencies."
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary handling of the case reflects its highly
charged political sensitivity. "It's fair to say that other
clemency cases to not raise the same questions as the case of Mr.
Pollard," Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Pollard, an former U.S. naval intelligence officer, is serving
a life sentence for handing over thousands of top-secret U.S.
documents to Israel in 1984 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, acting on Clinton's
behalf, sent letters Nov. 16 to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Defense Secretary William Cohen, CIA Director George
Tenet and Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
The letters asked for any information that might bear on
Clinton's consideration of clemency for Pollard along with any
recommendations they might wish to make, Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
The letter further requested that all relevant agencies,
including the FBI, Defense Intelligence Agency and National
Security Agency, be included in the process.
</P>
<P>
At the Wye Plantation talks, Tenet vehemently opposed Pollard's
release and told Clinton it would be impossible for him to
continue as director if the convicted spy were freed, according to
a Clinton administration official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
