<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Calls for Universal Ratification of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) has urged all states to sign and/or ratify
without delay the Convention on the Prohibition of the Use,
Stockpiling, Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and
on their Destruction if they have not yet done so.
</P>
<P>
The convention, known as Ottawa treaty, was signed by 123
states in Ottawa, Canada a year ago and the number of
ratifications (40) needed to bring the treaty into force was
reached on September 16, 1998, a record time for an arms-related
treaty.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the speed at which the Ottawa treaty has been
ratified, ICRC President Cornelio Sommaruga stressed here Thursday
that "landmines pay no attention to treaties".
</P>
<P>
"It is only when states fulfil their obligation to clear mines,
destroy stockpiles and assist victims that the treaty will begin
to save lives," said Sommaruga, adding that the real challenge was
to mobilize the resources needed to implement the Ottawa treaty at
national and international levels.
</P>
<P>
"The tragic lesson to be drawn from the recent floods in
Central America is that mines can go on many years after they
have been laid," said the ICRC president. "They can also travel to
areas many kilometers away. Every day counts."
</P>
<P>
A total of 131 states have now signed the treaty and 55 have
ratified it. The treaty will enter into force on March 1, 1999 for
the 40 states that ratified it by September 16, 1998. It takes six
months for a country which ratifies the treaty to implement it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
