<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Rejects U.S. Proposal Over Banana Regime Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
rejected on Thursday the United States' demand to change the EU's
banana regime.
</P>
<P>
The EU said it wishes to resume discussions to bridge the
differences once the EU and the U.S. have "agreed on a mutually
acceptable dispute settlement procedure."
</P>
<P>
In response to a letter from U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky, European Commission Vice-President Leon Brittan said
the United States apparently wants to break off negotiations and
resort to actions which may lead to a major trade dispute between
the EU and the United States and damage the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
He said he felt disappointed when he received the letter this
morning and knew the EU and the United States would not be able to
reach an agreement on a timetable for an accelerated WTO panel on
the EU banana regime.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said in his letter to Barshefsky that the EU does not
think it would make sense for the United States to take
retaliatory actions against the EU because its proposal provides
the United States with the opportunity to obtain a definitive,
independent resolution on a dispute that has been running for some
years.
</P>
<P>
The dispute might be settled in a few weeks after March 3,
1999, the deadline the United States set for resorting to
retaliatory actions.
</P>
<P>
However, the vice president said the EU "remains ready to
continue the discussions" if the United States would give its
decision a second thought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
