<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Annan's Planned Trip to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain welcomed on Thursday UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's announcement that he would visit
Libya to discuss the hand-over of two men who are responsible for
the Lockerbie airliner bombing.
</P>
<P>
The plan to try the Libyan suspects before a special court of
Scottish judges in the Netherlands was non-negotiable, a British
official said.
</P>
<P>
Annan announced on Thursday that he would travel to Libya on
Saturday to meet Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and discuss the
hand-over of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the secretary-general can persuade Gaddafi to reply
promptly so justice can be done," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi, who agreed to the trial plan in theory earlier this
year said last Sunday that Britain and the United States were
still trying to impose unacceptable conditions and were refusing
to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Britain promised Libya unrestricted consular
access to the suspects if they were jailed in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council imposed an air and arms embargo on
Libya, expanding it in 1993, to include a freeze on Libyan assets
abroad and a ban on oil equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
