<HEADLINE> UNESCO Adds New Entries to List of Cultural, Natural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A committee of the
United Nations Educational Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO) has expanded its list of cultural and natural sites
around the world that it designates as having "exceptional
universal value," a U.N. release said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO's World Heritage Committee, which has been meeting in
Kyoto, Japan, since November 30, added 30 new sites to its World
Heritage list, bringing the total number to 582 in 114 countries.
</P>
<P>
The new inscriptions, located in 21 countries, include 27
cultural sites and three natural sites. For the first time, the
list includes sites located in Belgium and Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
Among this year's additions are the archaeological sites of
Troy, in Turkey, the Summer Palace in Beijing, China, and the
prehistoric rock-art sites in Portugal's Coa Valley.
</P>
<P>
The three new natural sites are located in the Russian
Federation, Solomon Islands and New Zealand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
