<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Tory Party in Crisis After Lords Leader Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition
Conservative Party leader William Hague's leadership was in deep
crisis after five Conservative peers resigned on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy leader Lord Fraser and four other Tory peers resigned in
protest against Hague's decision on Wednesday to sack Tory's
leader in the House of Lords Viscount Cranborne.
</P>
<P>
Hague sacked Lord Cranborne after he brokered a deal with the
government - without his leader's authority - to keep 91
hereditary peers during the first phase of House of Lords reform.
The sacking plunged the Tory party into crisis.
</P>
<P>
Opposition frontbench spokesmen Lord Bowness, Lord Pilkington
and the Earl of Home quit their posts hours after Lord Fraser
announced he was standing down. Baroness Strange announced she was
quitting the Tory party for the crossbenches.
</P>
<P>
Even the man chosen to replace Viscount Cranborne, Lord
Strathclyde, revealed he had offered his resignation which had
been rejected by Hague who instead asked him to take over the top
job in the upper House.
</P>
<P>
Lord Fraser said Hague had made a "serious mistake" in sacking
Lord Cranborne and there was widespread speculation in Westminster
that Hague had lost his grip of his own party.
</P>
<P>
The Tory leader hit back, insisting he had the "emphatic
support" of his MPs.
</P>
<P>
"We had a serious problem yesterday and I have dealt with that.
I am going to rebuild my party on the basis of discipline whether
people like that or not," Hague said.
</P>
<P>
Even though most believe he will be able to remain as leader,
if for no other reason than the fact that there is no obvious
alternative candidate, there is little doubt his leadership has
suffered its most serious crisis yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
