<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster '99 Conf Scheduled in Nairobi in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The first East African
Conference on Disaster Management for Businesses is scheduled in
the Kenyan capital in February, 1999, the Nairobi-based Untied
Nations Center for Human Settlements (Habitat) said.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the conference is to bring together
professionals within the business community to share and learn
the lessons from the August 7 Nairobi bombing so that they can be
better prepared, the Habitat said in a press release available
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Topics to be discussed at the meeting will include
vulnerability analysis, insurance coverage, the implementation of
a business continuity plan, re-establishment of computer and
telecommunications system and protecting logistics lifelines.
</P>
<P>
Being prepared is not only good for businesses but also
benefits all people, Habitat acting Executive Director Klaus
Toepfer said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the business community have a critical role to
play in protecting their employees, customers and their
surrounding neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
International studies indicate that on average only 30 percent
of companies are still in operation within three years of a major
disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Habitat noted the key to survival depends largely upon the
ability to muster an immediate, effective and accurate response.
In short, the businesses cannot afford to be caught unprepared.
</P>
<P>
The conference is to be organized by the Financial Mail with
the support of Habitat and other organizations including Kenya
Airways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
