<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Parliamentarian Seminar Starts in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A two-day African
parliamentarian seminar began in Zimbabwean capital Harare
Thursday to discuss the role and functioning of parliaments in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwean Speaker of Parliament
Cyril Ndebele said that legislators should ensure their
independence by not relying solely on information provided by
lobbyists and agencies of the executive.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said there was an urgent need by African
parliaments to have an independent and comprehensive information
and research service from which the legislature could draw.
</P>
<P>
In most cases, he said, governments had a monopoly of
information which would be biased toward the executive.
</P>
<P>
Ndebele also said that democracy and good governance could not
flourish where decisions of national significance were made
secretly without consulting civil society.
</P>
<P>
He said strengthening legislature in developing countries
should not be seen as competition with the executive but was a
way to enable them to play their constitutional and complementary
roles in governance.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Global Coalition for Africa meeting was being
attended by participants from 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
It would focus on issues relating to competent functioning of
parliaments and development of expertise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
