<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Claims Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of first-time
applications for unemployment benefits rose last week, the Labor
Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jobless claims increased by 12,000 to a seasonally adjusted
313,000, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, it was still below the level of early November. But a
four-week moving average rose by 250 to a seasonally adjusted
319,250.
</P>
<P>
That was the highest level since July, when the General Motors
strikes increased the number of claims. Excluding the GM strike,
the four-week average hit a 10-month high.
</P>
<P>
Due largely to loss of sales abroad, primarily in East Asia,
the U.S. manufacturers had to slash payrolls by nearly 200,000
jobs and the nation's unemployment rate has crept to 4.6 percent
from a 28-year low of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest evidence of the negative impact came this week when
Boeing Co., the world's largest aerospace company, announced it
would lay off 20,000 workers, bringing its planned job cuts
announced since the summer to 48,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
