<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Presidential Ban on Strikes Tabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Ministry of Public
Service, Labor and Social Welfare Thursday tabled before
parliament the presidential powers (temporary measures)
regulations meant to ban strikes under the labor regulations.
</P>
<P>
The presidential decree comes at a time when actions by the
labor movement, the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions, are blamed
for inflicting huge damages on the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a parliamentary address regarding the presidential powers
promulgated on November 27 this year, Minister Florence Chitauro
said there were procedural requirements to amend a piece of
legislation and yet there was need to amend the law in order to
protect the economy, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The government, she said, could not wait for the amendment
processes of the labor relations act in order to include strikes
among illegal mass actions.
</P>
<P>
"These stay-aways have damaged the economy and the government
believes that the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions is taking
advantage of the inadequacies in our labor legislation, as the
current labor relations act does not adequately address the issue
of stay-aways," said Chitauro.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to bring on board the issue of stay-away
legislatively through the presidential powers does not mean that
the government had abandoned the much-cherished dialog," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
"It is merely a measure to govern a collective action which
was omitted and now being resorted by labor organization," she
said, adding that dialog would continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
