<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Urged Not to Deploy Russian Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has urged the Cypriot
government not to deploy Russian anti-aircraft missiles on the
island, U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill said here Thursday
after his meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
"We have always supported the idea of the missiles not
coming to Cyprus. As long as they are not coming to Cyprus,
we are ready to consider almost anything else," the Ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
And the U.S. supports the ongoing U.N.-sponsored shuttle talks
which Secretary-General Kofi Annan's envoy in Cyprus Dame Ann
Hercus is conducting, he added.
</P>
<P>
Brill said the arrival of the missiles "complicates the process
of getting to the demilitarization of Cyprus," adding that "we
hope that the position we have taken from the beginning that they
should not come to Cyprus is the one that will be adopted by the
government of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.N. process would be facilitated if the
missiles do not arrive in Cyprus, Brill said that the U.S.
would not want to see things happen that would detract from
that process.
</P>
<P>
"The arrival of the missiles would detract from that," he
stressed, noting that the ongoing U.N. process is all the
more reason for the U.S. position to be adhered to.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
anti-aircraft missiles in a bid to booster its defense.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other western countries have criticized Cyprus
for the deal, and Turkey have threatened to launch pre-emptive
military strikes if the missiles are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Brill said the U.S. initiative to break the current deadlock
in Cyprus runs parallel to that of the U.N. and expressed
strong support to the U.N. process.
</P>
<P>
"Dame Ann has the strongest possible support from the U.S.
government and other members of the U.N. Security Council," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
1974 following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the
island through a bi-communal formula, but no results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
