<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium on DU Impacts Concludes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- People who were affected by
depleted uranium (DU) in the 1991 Gulf War should be compensated,
said a statement issued here Thursday at the conclusion of an
international symposium on the use of DU and its impacts on man
and environment.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, which started on Wednesday,
participants discussed the grave effects of the U.S.-British use
of banned DU shells against Iraq on its coming generations and on
other states in the region.
</P>
<P>
The symposium brought together more than 200 experts and
specialists from the U.S., Britain, Canada, Germany, Jordan,
Tunisia and Iraq, and some U.S. and British veterans who had
participated in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Two sessions were held Thursday to discuss scientific research
findings on the issue. One research indicates that large
landscapes in southern Iraq have been polluted by DU radiations,
referring to the increase in cancer cases among Iraqi soldiers,
especially the spread of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
Another research shows that barrenness cases have more
than doubled in the Iraqi province of Basrah, and at the
same time, cases of congenital deformities have also doubled,
notably in the southern provinces.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. allegations that the Gulf War was a clean war
were not true, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait in August 1990, touching off the
1991 Gulf War. During the 43-day war, the U.S. and Britain
dropped some 700-800 tons of DU shells in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tietmeyer: Rate-Cutting not under Political Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- In a concerted action, 11 European
banks were cutting their key interest rates to a nearly-uniform
3.0 per cent on Thursday. But the German Bundesbank's president
Hans Tietmeyer promised at the same day, that was not owing to any
political pressure.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank cut its security repurchase offer - an
instrument providing short-term liquidity to banks - to 3.0 per
cent from the 3.30 per cent level which has been unchanged since
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Tietmeyer said the rate cut decision
had been taken after consultations with other 10 central banks as
well as with the European Central Bank (ECB), the institution
which on January 1, 1999 will be guiding the fortunes of the
European Monetary Union and the single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer stressed that the rate cut move of the German
Bundesbank, which took most financial market experts completely by
surprise, was a "sovereign decision of the Bundesbank,
uninfluenced by political expectations".
</P>
<P>
And that, all other 10 central banks lowered their rates, did
not take place due to political pressure, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer said that after intensive analysis by the ECB and the
Bundesbank, it was determined that a "further coordinated rate
cut is called for in order to guide downward the central banks'
rates at the start of the European Monetary Union to 3.0 per
cent".
</P>
<P>
The German Finance Ministry issued a statement at the same day
welcoming the rate cut, calling the decision one which would
contribute to more growth and employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
