<HEADLINE> "Devilish Lovers" Extradited Back to Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A Belgian couple, known as the
"Devilish Lovers" and suspected of killing their respective spouse
in order to claim colossal amounts of life insurance, were
extradited on Thursday from the United States to Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Aurore Martin and Peter Hue-Schmidt, detained in mid-November
1997 in Miami of the United States at the request of the Belgian
jurisdiction, were finally extradited to Brussels after 12 months
of legal entanglement.
</P>
<P>
The two was scheduled to be interrogated by Brussels' municipal
judge, Damien Vandermeersch.
</P>
<P>
Aurore Martin and Peter Hue-Schmidt were suspected of
murdering, via traffic accidents, their respective spouse in 1992
and then in 1995 so as to claim as much as a combined life
insurance of more than 40 million Belgian francs (1.1 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The two were accused of having planned to start a luxurious
life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Aurore Martin and Peter Hue-Schmidt team reportedly made
the most of the loopholes of American legislation to set back
their extradition back to Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
