<HEADLINE> LIFFE Trades Over 184 Million Contracts to Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) - The London International
Financial Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) traded 11,980,834
futures and options contracts during November 1998.
</P>
<P>
Average daily volume amounted to 570,516 contracts,
representing an average daily nominal turnover of 182 billion
pounds (291.2 billion US dollars), the LIFFE announced here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the year to date, January to the end of November,
LIFFE's cumulative volume totalled 184,423,442 contracts, 6
percent down on the same period last year, it added.
</P>
<P>
Open interest, a good indicator of liquidity and long term use
of the market, totalled 9,044,135 contracts on 30 november, an
increase of 22 percent from the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
Hugh Freedberg, LIFFE's Chief Executive, said "LIFFE's November
volumes reflected quiet underlying cash markets due to lower
volatility, ahead of the introduction of Economic and Mometary
Union."
</P>
<P>
However, with the introduction of a Three Month Euro Euribor
futures contract on 8 December, LIFFE will be offering the market
a complete range of euro-denominated money market contracts in the
run-up to EMU and beyond, Freedberg added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Confidence Falls in Britain at Record Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) - Confidence in high street sales
among British retailers is falling at its fastest rate since
records began 15 years ago, according to a survey by The
Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
Sales volumes were down, with only 36 percent of shops
reporting an increase compared with the same time last year and 45
percent experiencing a dip.
</P>
<P>
The CBI found that falling sales in November took retailers by
surprise and led them drastically to cut their expectations.
</P>
<P>
It said the survey underlined the need for a further cut in
interest rates at the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee
meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate director of economic
analysis, said the results "underlined the message from other
data, that demand at home is softening, supporting the need for a
0.5 percent cut in interest rates next week."
</P>
<P>
The survey came on the day that another poll found the service
sector as a whole had contracted for the first time in at least
two years.
</P>
<P>
The November Chartered Institute of Purchasing Managers' report
found business activity decreased for the first time since the
survey began in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
