migration agreements between the two countries, said State
Department spokesman James Foley.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the talks, the 10th in the current
series, will deal exclusively with migration issues. The U.S.
delegation will be led by John Hamilton, a deputy assistant
secretary
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the U.S. Coast Guard has been returning to the
island Cuban boat people who attempt to flee to the United States.
Cuba has promised not to punish those who are returned.
</P>
<P>
A recurring U.S. complaint is that the departure fees Cuba
charges to legal emigrants are excessive. A bilateral agreement
requires the United States to grant residence visas to 20,000
Cubans each year.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. concern is Cuba's unwillingness to allow the
return of some of the Cubans who arrived in the United States in
the 1980 Mariel boat-lift. 
