<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Annan Can Help Solve Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt hoped that U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan's upcoming visit to Libya would help seek a
solution to the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said all parties concerned
have the desire to end the standoff between Libya, on the one
hand, and the United States and Britain, on the other, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt hopes that the problem could be settled to
the satisfaction of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Annan is scheduled to arrive in Tripoli, capital of Libya on
Saturday to help solve the Lockerbie issue in which 270 people
were killed..
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain demanded that Libya surrender two of its
citizens suspected of blowing up the Pan Am 103 flight over
Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
For years, Washington and London insisted that the two suspects
be tried either in the U.S. or Scotland. Fearing that its citizens
will not get a fair trial, Libya refused to hand over the
suspects, demanding that they be tried in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain succeeded in pressing the U.N. Security
Council to impose an air and arms embargo on Libya in 1992 for its
refusal to extradite the suspects.
</P>
<P>
A compromise has been reached lately that the Libyan suspects
be tried in the Hague, the Netherlands by Scottish judges
according to Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Libya, meanwhile, seeks guarantee that the suspects will not be
extradited to the U.S. and wants them to be imprisoned in Libya if
convicted of guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
