<HEADLINE> Egypt's Human Rights Group Stops Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Organization for
Human Rights (EOHR) Thursday announced to freeze its activities in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In a board meeting, the organization's general assembly was
asked to meet within three months to review the decision.
</P>
<P>
The board denied once again any link between a check of 25,703
U.S. dollars EOHR received from the British embassy in Cairo and
its report on what it called religious prosecution in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
EOHR insisted that it has not conducted any activities that
might subject itself or any members to legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
EOHR's decision followed the detention of its secretary
general, Hafez Abu Saada, Wednesday, accused of "receiving foreign
funds with the intention of damaging national interests."
</P>
<P>
The private-owned Al Usbou weekly newspaper reported that EOHR
got the check from the British embassy after it released the
report alleging police torture of Christian Copts in southern
Egypt. The weekly described the report as treason.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper testified on October 25 to the Egyptian public
prosecution by showing a copy of the check and a copy of the
organization's report.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's higher State Security Court issued the detention
warrant Wednesday after questioning Abu Saada over the issue. He
would face seven to 15 years of hard labor if convicted, judicial
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Tuesday that EOHR in
its September report said that more than 1,000 Copts were rounded
up by security forces in Kosheh village in southern Suhag
Governorate.
</P>
<P>
Based on the allegation, Britain's Sunday Telegraph newspaper
reported that "Egyptian Christians have been subjected to horrific
crucification rituals, raped and tortured by the security forces
during a crackdown on the ancient Coptic community."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's parliament, social groups and celebrities have
denounced the story in the British newspaper as a fabrication
aimed at defaming Egypt.
</P>
<P>
They said that the Muslims and Christians have been co-existing
in peace for more than 14 centuries in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
