<HEADLINE> Egypt's Trade Deficit Rises in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's trade deficit in the
first eight months of 1998 was 28.22 billion Egyptian pounds (8.3
billion U.S. dollars), a 37.39 percent rise from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
A monthly report issued Thursday by the Cabinet Information and
Decision Support Center attributed the increase of the deficit to
the fall in export and rise in import, the Middle East News Agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Egypt exported 6.87 billion pounds (2.02
billion dollars) worth of goods in the January-August period, down
about 21 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports, on the other hand, rose about 20 percent from a
year earlier to reach 35.09 billion pounds (10.32 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Manufactured and semi-manufactured exports in the period stood
at 3.85 billion pounds (1.13 billion dollars), compared to 4.02
billion pounds (1.18 billion dollars) of the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Exports of raw materials and cotton was 845 million pounds
(248.5 million dollars), compared to 806 million pounds (237.1
million dollars) in the first eight months in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
