<HEADLINE> U.S. Has More Than 1.2 Million Abortions in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States had more
than 1.2 million abortions in 1996, or 20 abortions per 1,000
women aged 15 to 44, the government reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said there were
1,221,585 abortions in 1996, an increase of less than 1 percent
from the previous year. It was the first time abortions have not
declined since 1990, when the total was more than 1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
The nation legalized abortions nationally in 1973. Since then,
abortion rates had increased steadily until 1980, when they
reached 25 per 1,000 women aged 15 to 44. But they leveled off
through 1992, when rates began falling again.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press quoted the Centers as saying that the
decline may have been caused by a drop in unwanted pregnancies.
Abortion rights supporters have said there are also fewer clinics
performing abortions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
