<HEADLINE> Research Council Calls for Weather Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Research
Council called for increased climate research and the impact of
weather on human health in a report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the report entitled "The Atmospheric Sciences Entering The
21st Century," the council said that weather forecasts of the
future could include human health impacts, levels of various
pollutants and even the effect of changes in energy from the sun.
</P>
<P>
"Understanding the links between weather, climate and various
diseases and how they spread will require collaboration" among
various sciences, noted the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that temperature, rain, sunshine, wind,
humidity and soil moisture may well affect the emergence and
spread of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
It called for the study of space weather because variations in
the flow of energy from the sun can affect conditions on Earth,
particularly electronic communications by radio, television and
satellite.
</P>
<P>
The NRC is the research arm of the U.S. National Academy of
Sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
