<HEADLINE> New Degradable Plastic Launched in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A new degradable plastic,
launched Thursday in the UK which can disappear completely in as
little as 60 days, may mean an end to plastic pollutions.
</P>
<P>
Symphony Environmental Ltd, the British company which developed
the plastic, said that the innovation has profound implications
for post-consumer waste, especially in relation to food packaging
and its effect on the environment.
</P>
<P>
The plastic works by combining an additive with a blend of
polythene resins during the plastic production process. The
additive can "tell" the plastic when to start breaking down.
</P>
<P>
The degradation process begins during the normal usage of the
product with any combination of heat, light and stress acting as
catalysts.
</P>
<P>
Once the plastic is fully broken down, all that's left is a
negligible amount of water and carbon dioxide, the company told a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
The unique aspect of the new material is the controllable
nature of the degradation process. The timescale of degradation is
adjusted according to the application of the polythene film; for
example, bread bags and rubbish bags will have different life
spans.
</P>
<P>
When engineered, the material can degrade completely in as
little as 60 days or as long as five to six years depending on the
requirements of the product, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Markets Surge as Central Banks Cut rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Stock markets had a
roller-coaster ride Thursday as Europe's central banks unveiled a
coordinated cut in interest rates for the introduction of euro on
January 1.
</P>
<P>
In London the FTSE 100 index closed higher for the first time
in four sessions, up 1.1 percent after a roller-coaster session
boosted by the rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
As the market opened Thursday morning the index went into
instant freefall plunging 112.8 points in the opening few minutes.
</P>
<P>
But the tide turned late in the morning, as the concerted rate
cuts by euro-zone nations led by Germany fired volatile European
shares to higher closes.
</P>
<P>
A 7 percent rise in Royal Bank of Scotland shares helped boost
the bank sector, which accounted for some 20 points of the FTSE
100's rise.
</P>
<P>
Germany's blue-chip Xetra DAX index also turned early losses
into gains as central banks across Europe cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Index was up 2.1 percent at 4,812.00 points, rebounding
after spending most of the day in negative territory.
</P>
<P>
Among the big winners were Lufthansa which was up 6.2 percent
to DM 37.60, and Deutsche Telekom up 5.3 percent at DM 49.60
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, leading French stocks soared on the news
of the cuts, closing up 1.8 percent at 3,715.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the rate cut, share prices soared higher,
with leading stocks up 2.26 percent at 3,732.36 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
