<HEADLINE> EU Enhances Fight against Cartels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, December 3 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
competition commissioner Karel van Miert said here Thursday that
the union will continue its staunch fight against cartels which
are one of the most harmful restraints of trade.
</P>
<P>
To this effect, He said, it is necessary to form a new unit to
fight against cartels. The new unit, which has started its work
this week, is charged exclusively with unveiling, pursuing and
eliminating cartels for any product and service related
activities.
</P>
<P>
From now on, the new service will become the anchor of the
commission's ongoing fight against cartels, Van Miert said. About
20 experienced officials have been assigned to the new unit for
"complex and painful accurate investigations."
</P>
<P>
The commission pointed out that where cartels operate consumers
must pay higher prices than they would in the event of real
competition and do not benefit from technological improvements,
which manufactures would necessarily have to implement if only
they fought honestly for developing their companies and increasing
market share.
</P>
<P>
"This new administrative unit reflects the commission's
determination to give a clear political signal: unfortunately, to
this day too many companies are tempted by the apparently simple
implementation of agreements with competitors, without considering
the damage inflicted on all citizens," the commissionner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
