<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidd Takes Over as Blackburn Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Brian Kidd, right-hand man to
Manchester United manager Alex Ferguson, took over as boss for
Blackburn Rovers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Brian Kidd has accepted the position as manager of Blackburn.
He has signed a contract that will keep him here until June 30,
2002," said Rovers chief executive John Williams.
</P>
<P>
Kidd, United's assistant manager, agreed a four-year deal to
move up the road from Old Trafford after talks with Blackburn's
steel magnate owner Jack Walker.
</P>
<P>
The job became vacant after Blackburn sank to the bottom of
the league and sacked Roy Hodgson on November 21.
</P>
<P>
Walker will introduce Kidd to Rovers fans before Saturday's
home game with Charlton Athletic, but caretaker Tony Parkes will
stay in charge for that match.
</P>
<P>
Rovers moved swiftly after they were given permission to talk
to Kidd on Wednesday when United chief executive Martin Edwards
agreed to let Blackburn approach him.
</P>
<P>
Despite his success at United, Kidd has only limited
managerial experience gained during short spells at Barrow and
Preston North End in the mid-eighties.
</P>
<P>
Walker said: "I am delighted Brian has decided to join us. He
was always our first choice."
</P>
<P>
Kidd was expected to treble his 200,000 pounds (334,000
U.S.dollars) salary by moving to Ewood Park. He will also be
handed an open cheque book to ensure Blackburn beat the drop.
</P>
<P>
The move was a disappointment for Ferguson, who had been just
as keen to keep the man who has been his assistant since August
1991.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson said after Manchester United lost 3-1 to Spurs in the
League Cup quarter-finals on Wednesday that he did not want Kidd
to leave.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a terrible blow to lose Brian. A terrible blow to
the club and a terrible blow to me personally. We have a
fantastic working relationship."
</P>
<P>
Kidd is part of United folklore, scoring a goal on his 19th
birthday in Manchester United's 4-1 victory over Benfica in the
European Cup final at Wembley on May 29 1968.
</P>
<P>
He also played for Arsenal, Manchester City, Everton and
Bolton in a 15-year career which included two England caps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
