<HEADLINE> IMF May Postpone First Disbursement of Aid to Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The International
Monetary Fund (IMF) could delay the delivery of its first loan of
5.3 billion U.S. dollars to Brazil, according to a television
report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The "Globonews" channel quoted IMF sources as saying that the
organization was considering the move after the Brazilian Congress
rejected on Wednesday a government reform program for the pensions
system, supposed to be crucial for the budget adjustment plan.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment plan, subject to congressional approval, was the
basis for the negotiations that opened the doors for an
international rescue package of 41.5 billion dollars agreed upon
on November 13 by officials of the IMF and the largest Latin
American economy.
</P>
<P>
A earlier report had said that 5.3 billion dollars would be
available immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government announced, after the defeat in the
parliament, that it would study other ways to obtain the same
savings that could have guaranteed the reform to the pensions
system.
</P>
<P>
One possible way could be to cut investments in infrastructure,
according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
However, the announcement apparently failed to pacify local
stock markets, which on Thursday opened with a downward trend and
closed the day with big losses amid doubts generated by the
parliamentary rejection.
</P>
<P>
The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, the most important in Latin
America, closed with an 8.78 percent fall, while the Rio de
Janeiro market, the second largest in the country, dropped by 8.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The worries were echoed on the same day at the New York Stock
Exchange, which was down by 2.05 percent, under shadows cast by
the Brazilian adjustment and a 2.5 percent drop in Japan's gross
domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
