<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Accept Christmas Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The alliance of
Colombia's major rebel groups on Thursday accepted a national
"Christmas truce" requested last week by President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Builes, the governor of Antioquia, received a letter
from the United Self-Defenses of Colombia (AUC) declaring they
would abstain from launching attacks from December 20 to January 6
to give the country a peaceful Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Castano, the AUC's top commander, told Builes in the
letter that the Christmas ceasefire declaration was in response to
the passionate request from the president.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana's call, heeded by Congress representatives and the
Catholic Church of Colombia hierarchy, was in keeping with the
insurgents' tradition of declaring a unilateral and temporary
ceasefire during the Christmas and New Year festivals.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian Liberation Army (ELN), the second most important
guerrilla force in Colombia, stayed silent on the truce request.
</P>
</TEXT>
