<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Letter Bomb Found At Sydney Post Office: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A package containing a parcel
bomb was found and detonated by Australian police in Sydney
Friday, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation News Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, found at Darlinghurst Post Office in inner Sydney,
was similar to 26 other potentially lethal parcel bombs at
addresses in Sydney, Canberra, Melbourne and the tropical tourist
attraction city of Gold Coast since Monday.
</P>
<P>
The parcel bomb panic started when one package exploded at a
mail exchange center in Canberra on Wednesday, injuring two postal
workers. Another 22 packages were later found in the center.
</P>
<P>
The building in Crown Street in Sydney had been evacuated just
after 9 am (local time) when staff had discovered a suspicious
package, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The package had been detonated by the police bomb disposal and
rescue squad inside the post office late Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The package was one of the three suspicious parcels discovered
by Sydney police Friday, and the other two packages were found to
be false alarms, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday morning, police searched an evacuated train in a
railway station in southwest Sydney, and the Penrith branch of the
Australian Taxation Office in the city's far-western suburb amid
fears of possible bomb packages in the train or the office, but no
letter bombs were found.
</P>
<P>
Police Thursday named Colin George Dunstan, 43, a suspended tax
officer in Canberra, as the prime suspect and launched a
nationwide hunt for him.
</P>
<P>
Dunstan was once involved in a bitter workplace sexual
harassment case and is now considered suicidal.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Police Assistant Commissioner Bill Stoll
said there was no indication of politically motivated violence or
any connection with any terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the letter bomb scare spread to Darwin, Melbourne
and Sydney.
</P>
<P>
In Darwin, the country's northernmost port city, a suspicious
package prompted the evacuation of the Northern Territory's
Parliament House but bomb experts found the package was full of
leaflets.
</P>
<P>
A package similar of appearance to the bomb and addressed to
Victorian state government Minister Louise Asher at her office
caused an evacuation of Melbourne's ANZ Tower.
</P>
<P>
An empty briefcase caused the evacuation of a central business
district building in Sydney late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard Friday said Australia was
fairly free of modern day urban terrorism, but human nature could
become a lethal weapon.
</P>
<P>
Howard told Melbourne Radio 3AW that Australians had to pay the
price by living with higher levels of security at the moment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Smuggling Attempts Foiled at Jakarta Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Customs and Excise officers at
Soekarno-Hatta International Airport here foiled attempts to
smuggle historical artifacts, compact discs and dried marijuana in
the month of November, the Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The airport's head of customs and excise Heru Santoso said the
most valuable single haul of contraband consisted of antique
swords.
</P>
<P>
The consignment was uncovered on November 12, he said, adding
that the swords were in an airmail package sent from Medan in
North Sumatra to Madrid in Spain.
</P>
<P>
"It's the first airmail smuggling attempt we've ever been aware
of. Goods are usually smuggled in containers," Heru said.
</P>
<P>
The customs declaration stated that the package contained
souvenirs, however X-ray inspection revealed a number of swords.
</P>
<P>
Hari Untoro from the Ministry of Education and Culture's
directorate general for the protection of archeological goods said
the swords were very valuable.
</P>
<P>
Heru said his officers then foiled an attempt to smuggle 9,270
compact discs containing pirated computer software later the same
day.
</P>
<P>
Legitimate versions of the software would have retailed for a
combined total of 70 million U.S. dollars, he said, adding that
the haul included illegal copies of Auto Cad version 12, which
retails for 10,000 U.S. dollars a copy.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, a consignment of 1,100 pirated music compact
discs were intercepted, followed by 22,000 compact discs
containing pirated music and pornographic films on November 23.
Both shipments were destined for Singapore, Heru said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0357 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lay Assessors Should Have Legal Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Legal experts said that the
improvement of public awareness of the country's laws and
education in legal matters is the precondition for the proper
function of the people's lay assessor system, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"People's lay assessors must have certain educational level and
have some legal knowledge," said He Lianshui, attorney-at-law with
the Beijing Yuanwang Law Firm.
</P>
<P>
Many legal professionals maintain that, in cities like Beijing
and Shanghai, lay assessors should have a college education.
</P>
<P>
"Lay assessors should think independently, only when this is
achieved can the system function well," said Chen Ruihua, a law
professor with Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Since most lay assessors have no systematic legal education,
they feel intimidated in front of judges, especially if
disagreements arise, which often results in assessors just
listening to trials without making their own judgements.
</P>
<P>
Though insisting that the length of sentences requires in-depth
legal knowledge and should thus be left to judges, Chen said lay
assessors may prove to be even more objective than the judges in
determining the facts.
</P>
<P>
"People with certain experience in life and an ability to think
logically are capable of making judgements about facts," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
In cases involving sentences of five years' imprisonment or
more, he proposed that a jury of six lay assessors should be
formed in addition to the three judges.
</P>
<P>
Attorney He said the people's lay assessor system should work
well so long as it is adapted to the Chinese legal system.
</P>
<P>
The courts currently pay more attention to lay assessors'
proficiency in their individual fields than their legal knowledge,
said a judge from the intellectual property rights court in the
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court, adding that this helps
judges to determine the facts of a case.
</P>
<P>
The jury system was introduced to China at the beginning of
this century, but ended with the fall of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911), and China inherited the people's lay assessor system
from the former Soviet Union.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0358 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
