<HEADLINE> Disabled Try to Achieve Financial Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- "Disabled people are working
hard to improve their livelihoods and shrug off an image that they
are a burden to their families and society," said Wang Tiecheng, a
high official with the China Federation for Disabled Persons
(CFDP), according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The disabled in China are making solid efforts to achieve more
economic independence. Wang, together with other CFDP officials
and some relatives of disabled people, visited the Beijing
Sino-Norwegian Woollen Product Factory, a joint venture which
creates job opportunities mainly for mentally retarded people.
</P>
<P>
The factory, built with a 570,000 yuan(69,000 U.S.dollars)
investment from the Norway Disabled Persons' Organization this
year, employs 30 disabled people.
</P>
<P>
The employees learn to weave clothes on machines and other
basic skills with a monthly salary of 500 yuan (60 U.S.dollars),
said Yu Yong, the factory manager.
</P>
<P>
"Our factory has become a training centre for disabled
people. And it helps develop their potentials to become more
self-reliant,"said Yu.
</P>
<P>
The visit was a part of the celebration to mark the 7th
International Day for Disabled Persons yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
