<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Cut Import Duties in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian government is to
cut most import duties from January 1, 1999, in a bid to revive
its economy, according to a senior customs official.
</P>
<P>
The tariff reduction will be made on almost all imported goods
that Bulgaria itself does not produce, said Plamen Minev, chief of
the General Customs Directorate, following a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's average tariff in 1999 will be 15.58 percent,
compared to 17.25 percent in 1997 and 16.18 in 1998. The downward
tendency will continue in the next two years so as to reach the
standard in the European countries where duties charged on
industrial goods average 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency, the maximum tariff
of 74 percent will be charged on no more than 30 articles. Only
the tariff on cigarettes will go up due to considerably reduced
excise duties.
</P>
<P>
Duties on crude oil will keep their previous level of five
percent and those on petrol will drop from 25 to 22.5 percent.
Such imports as breeding animals, soy oil, and baby milks and
foods will be exempt from tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Also on the reduction list will be a number of industrial
goods, with the highest at 35 percent. The reduction, however,
does not cover ready-made clothes, shoes, household utensils and
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Almost all articles under the information technologies
agreement within the World Trade Organization, all raw materials
(apart from oil), medical equipment and medicines will be exempt
from customs charges.
</P>
<P>
The tariff on wheat, pork, sunflower oils and proteins for
fodder production are temporarily reduced in order to keep the
home market balance in conditions of liberal export regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressmen Visit Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Democratic Party
congressmen are now on a visit to Cuba, a Cuban Foreign Ministry
spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Representative Barbara Lee and Senator Christopher Dodd,
accompanied by their aides, came to the island country at the
invitation of the Cuban parliament, according Spokesman Alejandro
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was made to help the two congressmen know more
about Cuba and take home an objective idea of the country's
reality, said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Lee arrived in Cuba on Monday and is due to leave Saturday
while Dodd arrived on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
A group of U.S. lawmakers, joined by three former secretaries
of state, in October asked President Bill Clinton to reconsider
the U.S. policy toward Cuba, including the longstanding embargo
imposed almost 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The petition, which has not had an official response from the
White House, demands the creation of a bipartisan commission to
evaluate the American policy toward Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
