<HEADLINE> Canada, Switzerland Sign Agreement on Regulatory Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Switzerland signed an
agreement here Thursday on regulatory cooperation to boost
bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is structured to ensure that goods imported from
Switzerland meet all current Canadian safety requirements, and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
It pertains to products of telecommunications and information
technology, electrical safety, electro-magnetic compatibility,
medical devices, as well as manufacturing practices for
pharmaceutical goods.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Canadian International Trade
Minister Sergio Marchi and Swiss Federal Councillor and Head of
the Federal Department of Economic Affairs Pascal Couchepin, who
is making his first official visit to Canada.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement holds great promise for Canadian and Swiss
manufacturers alike," Marchi said in a release.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction of costs associated with meeting regulatory
requirements will go a long way to encourage and facilitate trade
between Canada and Switzerland," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Stars Plagued by Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Leander Paes and P. T. Usha,
the biggest names in the Indian delegation to the Asian Games,
have been troubled by injuries.
</P>
<P>
Men's tennis star Paes is unlikely to chase his goal of
three gold medals after suffering an ankle injury during the
world doubles championships last month.
</P>
<P>
Usha, former Asian athletics queen, may be denied a final Asian
Games gold medal by a hamstring injury she sustained in a domestic
 meet.
</P>
<P>
"We are keeping our fingers crossed about these two," an
Indian official said. "They will take part for sure but I am not
certain they can overcome these injuries to win gold medals."
</P>
<P>
Paes and his partner Mahesh Bhupathy, the world second-ranked
doubles pair, remain heavy favorites for the team and doubles
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Paes will have to withdraw from the singles event if he cannot
take the strain of three events.
</P>
<P>
The Indian star won the team and doubles events at the last
Asian Games in Hiroshima, Japan. But he lost the singles
semifinal to eventual winner Yong Yoon-il of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The day Usha was named in a 27-strong squad for the Bangkok
Games to run the 200- and 400-meter races and the two relays,
she suffered a hamgstring injury during a domesitic race in
Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
"I felt a pain on my right hamstring on the second bend, but
I kept on running," Usha said then. "The pain continued so I
stopped near the finish line to avoid further injury."
</P>
<P>
Usha surprised critics during the Asian track and field
championships in Fukuoka, Japan, in July this year with a gold and
silver in the realys and two bronze medals in the 200 and 400
meters.
</P>
<P>
Usha jumped to fame in the 1982 Asian Games in New Delhi, where
she won two silvers. She followed that with four golds and a
silver at the Seoul Games four years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
