<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressmen Visit Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Democratic Party
congressmen are now on a visit to Cuba, a Cuban Foreign Ministry
spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Representative Barbara Lee and Senator Christopher Dodd,
accompanied by their aides, came to the island country at the
invitation of the Cuban parliament, according Spokesman Alejandro
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was made to help the two congressmen know more
about Cuba and take home an objective idea of the country's
reality, said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Lee arrived in Cuba on Monday and is due to leave Saturday
while Dodd arrived on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
A group of U.S. lawmakers, joined by three former secretaries
of state, in October asked President Bill Clinton to reconsider
the U.S. policy toward Cuba, including the longstanding embargo
imposed almost 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The petition, which has not had an official response from the
White House, demands the creation of a bipartisan commission to
evaluate the American policy toward Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
