<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0375 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Foreign Trade Sharply Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's foreign trade,
including border trade, in the first eight months of this year
increased sharply over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official Economic Indicators issued by
the Central Statistical Organization, the total volume of foreign
trade in the period was 2.593 billion U.S. dollars, 41.38 percent
more than that of last year which was 1.834 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Export in the period amounted to 685 million dollars, while
import went to 1.908 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of the 658 million dollars worth of exported commodities, which
cover agricultural, marine and wood products, the state sector
shared 26.94 percent, while the private sector represented 72.32
percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.908 billion dollars worth of imported commodities,
which cover capital, intermediate and consumer goods, the state
sector shared 34.17 percent, while the private sector represented
65.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's foreign trade in
the 1997-98 fiscal year, which ended in March, totaled 3.24
billion dollars, of which export amounted to 1 billion dollars,
while import went to 2.24 billion dollars, registering a trade
deficit of 1.24 billion dollars despite increases in trade volume
by 12.8 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The country mostly traded with Asian countries which accounted
for about 80 percent of its total export value and about 86
percent of its total import value in the year.
</P>
<P>
Its major trading partners in Asia are China, India, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Myanmar enhanced cooperation in border trade
with its neighbors, opening up a total of 12 trade points -- six
with China, four with Thailand and one each with India and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar and India have agreed in principle to open
two more trade points by each side to boost their trade ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
