<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Central Bank Announces Cut in Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Spain on
Thursday announced an interest rate cut from five percent to three
percent, following similar cuts by other banks in the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank described the move as a concerted action with
the other 10 European countries that are to launch the single
currency on January 1 next year, as well as a "preventive" step in
response to the world financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
With the single exception of Italy, which cut its interest rate
to 3.5 percent on the same day, the other member countries of the
euro system have all lowered their interest rates to three percent.
</P>
<P>
The 11 euro countries are France, Germany, Italy, Spain,
Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Portugal, Austria, Finland
and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the Spanish Central Bank drew immediate
positive reaction from major stock markets across Europe, with the
Madrid stock exchange up by 1.14 percent, Frankfurt by 2.08
percent, Paris by 1.51 percent, Milan by 1.83 percent and London
by 0.67 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
