<HEADLINE> Major Smuggling Attempts Foiled at Jakarta Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Customs and Excise officers at
Soekarno-Hatta International Airport here foiled attempts to
smuggle historical artifacts, compact discs and dried marijuana in
the month of November, the Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The airport's head of customs and excise Heru Santoso said the
most valuable single haul of contraband consisted of antique
swords.
</P>
<P>
The consignment was uncovered on November 12, he said, adding
that the swords were in an airmail package sent from Medan in
North Sumatra to Madrid in Spain.
</P>
<P>
"It's the first airmail smuggling attempt we've ever been aware
of. Goods are usually smuggled in containers," Heru said.
</P>
<P>
The customs declaration stated that the package contained
souvenirs, however X-ray inspection revealed a number of swords.
</P>
<P>
Hari Untoro from the Ministry of Education and Culture's
directorate general for the protection of archeological goods said
the swords were very valuable.
</P>
<P>
Heru said his officers then foiled an attempt to smuggle 9,270
compact discs containing pirated computer software later the same
day.
</P>
<P>
Legitimate versions of the software would have retailed for a
combined total of 70 million U.S. dollars, he said, adding that
the haul included illegal copies of Auto Cad version 12, which
retails for 10,000 U.S. dollars a copy.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, a consignment of 1,100 pirated music compact
discs were intercepted, followed by 22,000 compact discs
containing pirated music and pornographic films on November 23.
Both shipments were destined for Singapore, Heru said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
