<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0383 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lay Assessors Should Have Legal Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Legal experts said that the
improvement of public awareness of the country's laws and
education in legal matters is the precondition for the proper
function of the people's lay assessor system, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"People's lay assessors must have certain educational level and
have some legal knowledge," said He Lianshui, attorney-at-law with
the Beijing Yuanwang Law Firm.
</P>
<P>
Many legal professionals maintain that, in cities like Beijing
and Shanghai, lay assessors should have a college education.
</P>
<P>
"Lay assessors should think independently, only when this is
achieved can the system function well," said Chen Ruihua, a law
professor with Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Since most lay assessors have no systematic legal education,
they feel intimidated in front of judges, especially if
disagreements arise, which often results in assessors just
listening to trials without making their own judgements.
</P>
<P>
Though insisting that the length of sentences requires in-depth
legal knowledge and should thus be left to judges, Chen said lay
assessors may prove to be even more objective than the judges in
determining the facts.
</P>
<P>
"People with certain experience in life and an ability to think
logically are capable of making judgements about facts," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
In cases involving sentences of five years' imprisonment or
more, he proposed that a jury of six lay assessors should be
formed in addition to the three judges.
</P>
<P>
Attorney He said the people's lay assessor system should work
well so long as it is adapted to the Chinese legal system.
</P>
<P>
The courts currently pay more attention to lay assessors'
proficiency in their individual fields than their legal knowledge,
said a judge from the intellectual property rights court in the
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court, adding that this helps
judges to determine the facts of a case.
</P>
<P>
The jury system was introduced to China at the beginning of
this century, but ended with the fall of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911), and China inherited the people's lay assessor system
from the former Soviet Union.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0384 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
