<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and the State
Council have issued a joint circular in their efforts to improve
the Party's work style and build an honest and clean government.
</P>
<P>
The circular outlined the responsibility that Party
committees, government and leading groups at various levels should
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading newspaper today frontpaged a commentary
which described the circular as a major step in the country's
campaign against corruption. It said that the circular also
indicated the determination of the Chinese government to carry out
anti-corruption drive by relying on a legal system.
</P>
<P>
-- At the invitation of the Central Committee of the Vietnamese
Communist Party and Vice President Nguyen Thi Binh of Vietnam, Hu
Jintao, member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party and vice
president of China, will pay an official visit to Vietnam from
December 17 to 19.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China values Morocco's positive role in regional and
international affairs and will strengthen coordination and
cooperation with Morocco in multi-lateral diplomacy to jointly
safeguard the rights and interests of developing countries
including China and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji made these remarks yesterday in his
talks with Prime Minister of Morocco Abderrahmane Youssoufi who
arrived in Beijing yesterday morning on a five-day official visit
as Zhu's guest.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing left Beijing on Thursday for
an official visit to Thailand and to attend the opening ceremony
of the 13th Asian Games scheduled for December 6 in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Li has been invited by Thai Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai
Rattakul.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Nationwide reforms in grain marketing have dramatically
reduced government losses resulting from grain purchases,
according to a China Agricultural Development Bank (CADB)
statistics report.
</P>
<P>
-- More foreign experts will be invited to China following the
annual "match-making" gathering which concluded yesterday in the
coastal city of Dalian, Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting attracted 400 representatives from foreign
experts' agencies and enterprises across China and 20 experts'
organizations from 13 countries. 
</P>
