<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0397 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Rejoins NBA Labor Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan returned to
join the NBA labor talks Thursday when the season looks in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
His agent said he wouldn't get involved again until
discussions got serious.
</P>
<P>
"His understanding was that a new proposal was going to be
made by the owners," said agent David Falk. "He wanted to be
there to listen to it. You can read into it that he's continuing
to be involved and supportive of the union leadership."
</P>
<P>
After about six hours of talks, neither side had put anything
new on the table.
</P>
<P>
The bargaining session was the first in 13 days with both full
negotiating committees in attendance. If the owners and players
can't come up with a solution in the next few weeks, the entire
1998-99 season likely will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
The last time Jordan attended a bargaining talk was October
28. He spent more than 8 hours to help reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
Jordan left early in the evening, and it was unclear if he
would return.
</P>
<P>
The sides spent the first two hours merely "feeling each other
out," commissioner David Stern said. No improvement after the
lunch break. 
</P>
</TEXT>
