<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Nonperforming Loans Up in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Nonperforming loans of
commercial banks in the Philippines inched up to 11.04 percent in
September, from 10.5 percent in August, as interest rates on loans
and other production costs continue to hurt business.
</P>
<P>
But the Business World Friday cited Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson as saying that the rate is still lower than that
of other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The uptick in nonperforming loans is consistent with the
central bank's expectations of a 0.5 percent to one-percentage
point increase monthly, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that of the country's 24 commercial and thrift
banks that suffered problems after the regional crisis broke out,
only two needed to be closed.
</P>
<P>
Other bankers believe that the nonperforming loan level in the
country will continue to rise up to the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Land Bank of the Philippines President Florido Casuela
predicted that the nonperforming loan level will peak at 14
percent to 15 percent as banks declare more losses due to
continued weak economic performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
