<HEADLINE> European Markets Surge as Central Banks Cut rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Stock markets had a
roller-coaster ride Thursday as Europe's central banks unveiled a
coordinated cut in interest rates for the introduction of euro on
January 1.
</P>
<P>
In London the FTSE 100 index closed higher for the first time
in four sessions, up 1.1 percent after a roller-coaster session
boosted by the rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
As the market opened Thursday morning the index went into
instant freefall plunging 112.8 points in the opening few minutes.
</P>
<P>
But the tide turned late in the morning, as the concerted rate
cuts by euro-zone nations led by Germany fired volatile European
shares to higher closes.
</P>
<P>
A 7 percent rise in Royal Bank of Scotland shares helped boost
the bank sector, which accounted for some 20 points of the FTSE
100's rise.
</P>
<P>
Germany's blue-chip Xetra DAX index also turned early losses
into gains as central banks across Europe cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Index was up 2.1 percent at 4,812.00 points, rebounding
after spending most of the day in negative territory.
</P>
<P>
Among the big winners were Lufthansa which was up 6.2 percent
to DM 37.60, and Deutsche Telekom up 5.3 percent at DM 49.60
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, leading French stocks soared on the news
of the cuts, closing up 1.8 percent at 3,715.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the rate cut, share prices soared higher,
with leading stocks up 2.26 percent at 3,732.36 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
