<HEADLINE> Duelfer Denies Meeting With Iraq's Dissidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Charles Duelfer, An
American and deputy chairman of the Untied Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM), on Thursday denied Iraq's charges that he met
last week with Iraq's dissidents.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz sent a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan this morning, charging that Duelfer
met dissident groups seeking the overthrow of Iraq's President
Saddam Hussein while he was in London last week.
</P>
<P>
Duelfer said it was coincidental he was in London on the same
day several Iraqi opposition groups met a top-ranking U.S. State
Department official.
</P>
<P>
Duelfer said he was in London on November 24 to meet with
British government officials on UNSCOM business and did not meet
with groups opposed to Iraq's Government.
</P>
<P>
Duelfer said he did not know of a meeting of Iraqi dissident
groups in London until he saw a television report.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Ambassador to the United Nations Nizar Hamdoon said the
main thrust of Aziz's letter was that Americans serving with UNSCOM
are actively seeking to push Washington's agenda while serving
with the U.N. and UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
"Duelfer is an international officer. He should not get
involved in anti-Iraqi campaigns. Iraq is considering these
types of activities of UNSCOM as being inconsistent with the
mandate of UNSCOM," Hamdoon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
