<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0422 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. FAA Orders Airlines to Keep Fuel in Tanks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration on Thursday ordered airlines to keep fuel in the
center tanks on Boeing 747s to prevent sparks by shaft bearings
in the tank's fuel pump when the tank is dry.
</P>
<P>
The agency also ordered airlines flying the 747-400 series,
planes with unique turned-up edges on their wings, to stop using a
fuel tank in the base of the plane's tail for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
The FAA made the orders after mechanics recently found wear in
pumps that after only 200 hours of operation although the pumps
normally operate for at least 20,000 hours before they are
removed.
</P>
<P>
The FAA is concerned that if the pump is run after the tank is
dry, the metal-on-metal contact could throw off sparks. There are
about 700 suspect bearings in new and overhauled pumps and part
kits.
</P>
<P>
The FAA orders apply immediately to all 246 U.S-registered
747s. There are 1,087 Boeing 747s worldwide. FAA orders do not
apply to foreign aircraft, but foreign aviation agencies usually
follow FAA suggestions on safety matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981204.0423 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
